s woman's part|date={{date|1939-09-09}}|p=4}}\n* {{note label|daily-telegraph|1934|\u03bb}} {{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article246678043|publisher=[[Australian Consolidated Press]]|publication-place=Sydney|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|department=Women In Sport|title=Long athletic season ahead|date={{date|1934-10-30}}|p=16}}\n* {{note label|smh-april-1937|\u03bc}} {{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17359298|publisher=Fairfax|publication-place=Sydney|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|title=These women have unusual occupations: shipboard wireless and market research, inducing people to travel|date={{date|1937-04-13}}|p=4}}\n* {{note label|smh-november-1938|\u03bd}} {{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17538480|publisher=Fairfax|publication-place=Sydney|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|title=Women will talk to women: How market research works, good shoppers wanted|date={{date|1938-11-17}}|p=22}}\n* {{note label|table-talk-1929|\u03be}} {{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article146726311|work=[[Table Talk (magazine)|Table Talk]]|department=Family Notices|title=Wentworth&mdash;Ashby|publication-place=Melbourne|date={{date|1929-03-14}}|p=64}}\n* {{note label|weekly-times-1946|\u03bf}} {{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article224429958|format=image|publication-place=Melbourne|work=Weekly Times|title=Miss Sylvia Ashby|date={{date|1946-07-03}}|p=26}}\n* {{note label|womens-weekly-1961|\u03c0}} {{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article51185968|work=[[Australian Women's Weekly]]|title=Worth Reporting|date={{date|1961-11-01}}|p=14}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ashby, Sylvia Rose}}\n\n[[Category:1908 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian women in business]]\n[[Category:Market researchers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian women]]\n", "name_user": "Chris.sherlock", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sylvia_Rose_Ashby"}
{"title_page": "Konkoly Observatory", "text_new": "{{lead too short|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox observatory\n| name            = \n| image           = 12csillagvizsg\u00e1l\u00f3civertanl\u00e9gi.jpg\n| caption         = Aerial photo of the 60 cm Heyde dome at Konkoly Observatory\n| organization    = [[Hungarian Academy of Sciences]]\n| abbreviation    = \n| location        = \n| coordinates     = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| altitude        = \n| weather         = \n| established     = {{Start date|1871}}\n| closed          = \n| website         = {{URL|http://www.konkoly.hu/index_en.shtml|Konkoly Observatory}}\n| telescope1_name = \n| telescope1_type = \n| telescope2_name = \n| telescope2_type = \n| telescope3_name = \n| telescope3_type = \n| telescope4_name = \n| telescope4_type = \n}}\n\n'''Konkoly Observatory''' ({{lang-hu|Konkoly Obszervat\u00f3rium}}; [[List of observatory codes|obs.&thinsp;code]]: [[IAU code#053|053]]) is an [[astronomy|astronomical]] [[observatory]] owned and operated by the [[Hungarian Academy of Sciences]], located in [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]]. It was founded in 1871 by Hungarian astronomer [[Mikl\u00f3s Konkoly-Thege]] (1842\u20131916) as a private observatory, and was donated to the state in 1899.<ref name=official_website>{{cite web|title=Konkoly Observatory of the Hungarian Academy of Sciences|url=http://www.konkoly.hu/index_en.shtml|website=www.konkoly.hu|accessdate=18 August 2017}}</ref> Konkoly Observatory, officially known as ''MTA CSFK Konkoly Thege Mikl\u00f3s Csillag\u00e1szati Int\u00e9zete'' in Hungarian, is the largest astronomical research institute in Hungary, and hosts the largest telescopes in the country.\n\nAs well as performing astronomical research, the observatory publishes the [[Information Bulletin on Variable Stars]] on behalf of the [[International Astronomical Union]].<ref name=official_website/>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== The \u00d3gyalla and Sv\u00e1bhely Observatories ===\nHungarian nobleman Mikl\u00f3s Konkoly-Thege founded his private observatory in 1871 at [[Hurbanovo]], in Northern Hungary, known as \u00d3gyalla in Hungarian at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.konkoly.hu/staff/balazs/100ev.html|title=100 \u00e9ves az MTA Csillag\u00e1szati Kutat\u00f3int\u00e9zete|last=Bal\u00e1zs|first=Lajos|date=1999}}</ref> The instrumentation included a 6\" [[Refracting telescope|refractor]], a 10.5\" Browning [[Reflecting telescope|reflector]] (later replaced with a 10\" Merz refractor), a [[meridian circle]], a spectrograph, as well as various meteorological and geomagnetic instruments. Konkoly-Thege, who had no offspring, became increasingly afraid over time that his legacy will perish with his death. As a member of the Hungarian Parliament, he was able to convince the government to take the observatory into state property. In 1899, the Hurbanovo site was renamed to Royal Konkoly-founded Astrophysical Observatory, and operated under the direction of Konkoly-Thege and Rad\u00f3 K\u00f6vesligethy, a renowned geophysicist of the time. The main scientific profile of the institute was the photometry of stars, the observation of the Sun, meteor counting, and providing time service for the government. In 1913, an order for a 60&nbsp;cm (24\") telescope was finalized with the German Heyde company, but with the start of [[World War I]], the telescope was never built.\n\nAfter the end of World War I, \u00d3gyalla became part of the newly formed [[Czechoslovak Republic (1918\u20131938)|Czechoslovak Republic]]. The government transferred the scientific equipment to Budapest before the newly formed border was shut down, and in 1921 allocated a new property in the [[Buda Hills|Buda hills]] just west to Budapest to build a new astronomical observatory. The new building, known as the Sv\u00e1bhegy observatory after a nearby hill, was finished by 1924, and the 6\" refractor and the re-ordered 60&nbsp;cm Heyde telescope were set up in new domes by 1928. Scientific work in the observatory focussed on the light variations of [[Variable star|pulsating stars]], the orbits of [[binary star]]s, and searching for [[asteroid]]s. Measurements were made with [[photographic plate]]s and wedge photometers.\n\nThe observatory survived [[World War II]] with minor damages. In late 1944, observations were put on hold, and the optical elements of the telescopes were removed to protect them from aerial bombings. Soviet troops occupied the buildings from December 1944 until February 1945, but the library and the photographic laboratories were spared. Observations were resumed by July 1945.\n\nAfter the communist takeover of Hungary in 1948, a new network of research institutes, independent from universities, was set up under the [[Hungarian Academy of Sciences]] (HAS). The observatory was renamed to the Astronomical Institute of the HAS, but retained the traditional name, Konkoly Observatory, in English correspondences. With the communist isolation of the country, international relations shifted from predominantly German and American to Soviet and [[Eastern Bloc|Eastern-bloc]] partnerships. However, the international recognition of then director [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Detre (astronomer)|L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Detre]] kept some connections to the West alive. During one of his visits to the Western bloc, Detre received an RCA 1P21 photomultiplier tube from American astronomer [[Harlow Shapley]]  to start photometric measurements at the observatory in 1948. He subsequently smuggled in to the country despite the strict trade restrictions at the time. In 1957, after the launch of Sputnik, multiple independent satellite observing and tracking stations were set up in the country at the suggestion of the Soviet Union. The institute provided coordination for these stations, and in 1966, the [[Baja, Hungary|Baja]] station merged into the institute.\n\nRelations with the West soon eased and at the 1961 General Assembly of the [[International Astronomical Union]] at Berkeley, the institute was tasked with setting up and circulating the ''Information Bulletin on Variable Stars''. The Bulletin was envisaged to be a rapid communications platform between variable star observers, but it later expanded into a peer-reviewed journal for short papers and notes about variable stars.\n\nThe institute expanded in the 1960-70s with the foundation and subsequent independence of the [[Debrecen Heliophysical Observatory]] and the installation of new telescopes at Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151 Mountain Station. In 1982, the observatories in Debrecen and Budapest were merged back together to form the Research Institute for Astronomy of the HAS. In 1992, the Baja station was separated from the institute and handed over to the county council of [[B\u00e1cs-Kiskun County|B\u00e1cs-Kiskun]].\n\nIn 2012, the Hungarian Academy of Sciences reorganized the structure of its institute network:<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nature.com/news/rhapsody-for-hungarian-science-1.9619|title=Rhapsody for Hungarian science|last=Schiermeier|first=Quirin|date=12 December 2011|work=Nature News}}</ref> the Astronomical Institute was merged with three other entities (Institutes for Geography, Geochemistry, and Geodesy and Geophysics) to form the Research Center for Astronomy and Earth Sciences.\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" widths=\"600\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Konkoly-main-building.jpg|The main building of the observatory.\nFile:Konkoly domes.jpg|Telescope domes at Konkoly Observatory in Budapest. From left: the 6\", 7\" and 24\" domes. The latter houses the 60&nbsp;cm Heyde refractor.\n</gallery>\n\n=== Debrecen Heliophysical Observatory ===\n{{main|Debrecen Heliophysical Observatory}}\nIn 1946, a new Solar physics department was initiated under the leadership of L\u00f3r\u00e1nt Dezs\u0151. In 1958, the department moved to [[Debrecen]] to form a new solar observatory independent of the Astronomical Institute. Observations of the Sun started with two photoheliograph telescopes, one of which was relocated to the top of the water tower at [[Gyula, Hungary|Gyula]] in 1972. In 1973, a large [[coronagraph]] telescope with a 53&nbsp;cm aperture was set up, but observations were hindered by the cumbersome mechanical setup. Given the low elevation of the observatory of just 124 m above sea level, the coronagraph was only capable to observe the [[chromosphere]] of the Sun, not the [[solar corona|corona]] itself.\n\nThe main scientific output of the observatory has been the detailed documentation of the [[Photosphere|photospheric]] activity of the Sun.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fenyi.solarobs.csfk.mta.hu/en/databases/Summary/|title=Summary table of databases at the Debrecen Observatory|last=Baranyi|first=T\u00fcnde}}</ref> The positions, sizes, structures of sunspots and sunspot groups are determined and recorded daily, to provide long-term, homogeneous observations of the Sun. The Debrecen Photoheliographic Data (DPD) database is the direct continuation of the [[Royal Observatory, Greenwich|Greenwich]] Photoheliographic Results that were collected between 1874-1976. Originally, analog [[Photographic plate|photographs]] and [[Charge-coupled device|CCD]] images were collected locally, or from partner observatories, but with the advent of reliable space-based observations, the work transitioned to the analysis of images from the [[Solar and Heliospheric Observatory|SOHO]] and [[Solar Dynamics Observatory|SDO]] spacecrafts. Further data products include the reanalysis of the Greenwich catalog, and older observations based on Hungarian drawings of the Sun.\n\nIn 1982, the observatory merged back into the Konkoly Astronomical Institute, and became a department of it once again. In 2015, the old observatory building in Debrecen was deemed unfeasible to maintain, and was closed down. The coronagraph was disassembled, and offices and personnel were transferred to the [[ATOMKI]] institute of the HAS in Debrecen. Given that space-based imagery has superseded the ground-based observations as the input source of the databases, the two photoheliographs were also decommissioned and removed from their mounts at Debrecen and Gyula.\n\n=== Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151 Mountain Station ===\n{{main|Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151 Station}}In 1951, the observatory secured funding for a new mapping telescope. The initial order was for a 0.9 m, f/3 Sonnefeld telescope but it was soon modified for a 60/90 com [[Schmidt camera|Schmidt telescope]]. With the light pollution of Budapest steadily increasing, a more remote location was sought for the telescope. After settling for Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151 peak in the [[M\u00e1tra|M\u00e1tra mountains]], about 80&nbsp;km away from the capital, a residence building was constructed in 1960, and the new Schmidt telescope was installed in 1962. The telescope provided a 10\u00b0x10\u00b0 field of view with photographic plates and could be equipped with an objective prism for low-resolution mass spectroscopic observations. The large field-of-view led to numerous supernova and asteroid discoveries at the time.\n\nIn 1966, a smaller, 0.5 m Cassegrain telescope with a two-channel photoelectric photometer was installed.\n\nFinally, a 1 m [[Ritchey\u2013Chr\u00e9tien telescope|Ritchey-Chr\u00e9tien]]-[[Coud\u00e9 telescope|coud\u00e9]] (RCC) telescope was installed in 1974, for high-resolution imaging and photometry of fainter targets. This marked the end of the initial development of Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151 station.[[File:Piszkesteto-observatory.jpg|alt=Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151 Mountain Station|thumb|300x300px|Aerial image of Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151 Mountain Station of the Konkoly Observatory in the M\u00e1tra hills.]]\n\nIn the late 1990s, photographic plates and photometers were replaced with CCD cameras on the Schmidt and RCC telescopes. In 2015, an echelle spectrograph with a spectral resolution of R=20,000 was installed on the RCC telescope.\n\nA 40&nbsp;cm Ritchey-Chr\u00e9tien telescope was set up in 2010, intended for automated remote observations. The telescope is currently under refurbishment.\n\nThe Fly's Eye system, consisting of 19 small cameras to observe the whole sky above 30\u00b0 altitude simultaneously, was installed in 2016.\n\nA new, automated 0.8 m telescope to track transient events, e.g., supernovae, is expected to be installed in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mta.hu/mta_hirei/szupernovak-gammakitoresek-fekete-lyukak-ket-komoly-robottavcso-epul-magyarorszagon-a-legizgalmasabb-csillagaszati-jelensegek-megfigyelesere-107372|title=Szupern\u00f3v\u00e1k, gammakit\u00f6r\u00e9sek, fekete lyukak: k\u00e9t komoly robott\u00e1vcs\u0151 \u00e9p\u00fcl Magyarorsz\u00e1gon a legizgalmasabb csillag\u00e1szati jelens\u00e9gek megfigyel\u00e9s\u00e9re|last=J\u00f3zsef|first=Vink\u00f3|date=7 February 2017|work=MTA H\u00edrek}}</ref>\n\nPiszk\u00e9stet\u0151 also hosts other instrumentations, including a [http://www.seismology.hu/index.php/en/home/live-seismograms seismic] and gravimetric station of the Institute for Geophysics and Geodesy, and an infrasound detector array.\n\n== Main research areas ==\n* Variable stars, stellar photometry, space-based photometry, exoplanets.\n* Astrochemistry, nuclear astrophysics, stellar dust. Includes the RADIOSTAR (Radioactivities from Stars to Solar Systems) [[European Research Council|ERC]] project.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mta.hu/mta_hirei/mi-volt-itt-a-naprendszer-elott-nyertes-erc-palyazat-az-mta-csfk-ban-107188|title=Mi volt itt a Naprendszer el\u0151tt? \u2013 Nyertes ERC-p\u00e1ly\u00e1zat az MTA CSFK-ban|date=5 December 2016|work=MTA H\u00edrek}}</ref>\n* Fly's Eye group: instrumentation and time-domain astronomy.\n* Small bodies in the Solar system: moons, TNOs, centaurs, comets, near-Earth asteroids, debris disks around other stars.\n* Protoplanetary disks and planet formation, star formation, infrared astronomy. Includes the SACCRED (Structured Accretion Disks) ERC project.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mta.hu/mta_hirei/harom-magyar-kutato-az-erc-starting-grant-idei-nyertesei-kozott-106775|title=Bolyg\u00f3keletkez\u00e9s, \u00fczemanyag f\u00fcstb\u0151l, tanul\u00e1s \u00e9s figyelem: h\u00e1rom magyar kutat\u00f3 az ERC Starting Grant 2016-os nyertesei k\u00f6z\u00f6tt|date=29 August 2016|work=MTA H\u00edrek}}</ref>\n* Solar and stellar activity, Doppler-imaging, differential rotation in stars, magnetic activity and dynamos, sunspot tracking.\n* Laboratory astrophysics and geochemistry, meteorites, planetary surfaces.\n* High-energy astrophysics, statistics of gamma-ray bursts.\n* Transient astrophysical objects (GINOP program).\n* Cosmic effects and risks (GINOP program).\n\n== Nomenclature ==\nThe observatory has had many different designations over the years. The current formal designation of the observatory is \"Konkoly Observatory, Research Centre for Astronomy and Earth Sciences, Hungarian Academy of Sciences\" ({{lang-hu|Magyar Tudom\u00e1nyos Akad\u00e9mia Csillag\u00e1szati \u00e9s F\u00f6ldtudom\u00e1nyi Kutat\u00f3k\u00f6zpontja, Konkoly Thege Mikl\u00f3s Csillag\u00e1szati Int\u00e9zet}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konkoly.hu/general.shtml|title=Konkoly Observatory of the Hungarian Academy of Sciences|website=www.konkoly.hu|accessdate=18 August 2017}}</ref> A former name, ''[http://svabhegyicsillagvizsgalo.hu/ Sv\u00e1bhegyi Csillagvizsg\u00e1l\u00f3]'', has been revived and used as branding for the public events and exhibitions hosted in the observatory and the 24\" inch dome in particular.\n\n== Publications ==\nThe observatory publishes multiple [http://konkoly.hu/publications_hun.shtml periodicals]. The most important one is the ''Information Bulletin on Variable Stars'', established by the [[International Astronomical Union|IAU]] in 1961 that contains peer-reviewed papers about variable star research and discoveries. Since 2011, IBVS is published as an online-only, [[Open access|open-access]], [[Article processing charge|APC]]-free journal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oastories.org/2011/09/hungary-journal-information-bulletin-on-variable-stars/|title=International Bulletin on Variable Stars: Fast, free and fifty: an open access star|date=September 2011|website=Open Access Success Stories}}</ref>\n\nLarger amounts of observational data and proceedings of meetings and conferences have been published in the ''Communications of the Konkoly Observatory'' (originally published under various Hungarian and German titles, like ''Mitteilungen der Sternwarte Budapest/Sv\u00e1bhegy,'' and later as ''Mitteilungen der Sternwarte der Ungarishen Akademie der Wissenshaften''). The observatory also published a few issues of ''Monographs'' (for History of Astronomy topics) and ''Occasional Technical Notes''.\n\n== Equipment ==\nCurrent equipment and locations:\n* 1 m RCC telescope (Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151). The main instrument, equipped with a medium-resolution echelle spectrograph and an EMCCD camera. \n* 60/90 Schmidt telescope (Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151). \n* 50&nbsp;cm Cassegrain telescope (Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151). Under renovation.\n* 40&nbsp;cm Ritchey-Cr\u00e9tien telescope (Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151). Under renovation.\n* [http://flyseye.net Fly's Eye] all-sky camera system (Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151).\n* 80&nbsp;cm telescope - under acquisition, to be installed at Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151.\n* [http://konkoly.hu/24 60 cm Heyde] Newton/Cassegrain telescope (Budapest). Decommissioned after 2013, it is being renovated for public demonstrations.\n* 7\" coud\u00e9 refractor (Budapest). Decommissioned.\n* coronagraph. Originally in Debrecen, decommissioned and disassembled.\n* 5\" photoheliograph (Debrecen). Decommissioned.\n* 6\" photoheliograph (Gyula). Decommissioned.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Open access in Hungary]] (publishing)\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.konkoly.hu/ Konkoly Observatory]\n* [http://www.konkoly.hu/staff/kollath/thefirst.html History of Konkoly]\n* [http://www.konkoly.hu/IBVS/IBVS.html Information Bulletin on Variable Stars]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Astronomical observatories in Hungary]]\n", "text_old": "{{lead too short|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox observatory\n| name            = \n| image           = 12csillagvizsg\u00e1l\u00f3civertanl\u00e9gi.jpg\n| caption         = Aerial photo of the 60 cm Heyde dome at Konkoly Observatory\n| organization    = [[Hungarian Academy of Sciences]]\n| abbreviation    = \n| location        = \n| coordinates     = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| altitude        = \n| weather         = \n| established     = {{Start date|1871}}\n| closed          = \n| website         = {{URL|http://www.konkoly.hu/index_en.shtml|Konkoly Observatory}}\n| telescope1_name = \n| telescope1_type = \n| telescope2_name = \n| telescope2_type = \n| telescope3_name = \n| telescope3_type = \n| telescope4_name = \n| telescope4_type = \n}}\n\n'''Konkoly Observatory''' ({{lang-hu|Konkoly Obszervat\u00f3rium}}; [[List of observatory codes|obs.&thinsp;code]]: [[IAU code#053|053]]) is an [[astronomy|astronomical]] [[observatory]] owned and operated by the [[Hungarian Academy of Sciences]], located in [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]]. It was founded in 1871 by Hungarian astronomer [[Mikl\u00f3s Konkoly-Thege]] (1842\u20131916) as a private observatory, and was donated to the state in 1899.<ref name=official_website>{{cite web|title=Konkoly Observatory of the Hungarian Academy of Sciences|url=http://www.konkoly.hu/index_en.shtml|website=www.konkoly.hu|accessdate=18 August 2017}}</ref> Konkoly Observatory, officially known as ''MTA CSFK Konkoly Thege Mikl\u00f3s Csillag\u00e1szati Int\u00e9zete'' in Hungarian, is the largest astronomical research institute in Hungary, and hosts the largest telescopes in the country.\n\nAs well as performing astronomical research, the observatory publishes the [[Information Bulletin on Variable Stars]] on behalf of the [[International Astronomical Union]].<ref name=official_website/>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== The \u00d3gyalla and Sv\u00e1bhely Observatories ===\nHungarian nobleman Mikl\u00f3s Konkoly-Thege founded his private observatory in 1871 at [[Hurbanovo]], in Northern Hungary, known as \u00d3gyalla in Hungarian at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.konkoly.hu/staff/balazs/100ev.html|title=100 \u00e9ves az MTA Csillag\u00e1szati Kutat\u00f3int\u00e9zete|last=Bal\u00e1zs|first=Lajos|date=1999}}</ref> The instrumentation included a 6\" [[Refracting telescope|refractor]], a 10.5\" Browning [[Reflecting telescope|reflector]] (later replaced with a 10\" Merz refractor), a [[meridian circle]], a spectrograph, as well as various meteorological and geomagnetic instruments. Konkoly-Thege, who had no offspring, became increasingly afraid over time that his legacy will perish with his death. As a member of the Hungarian Parliament, he was able to convince the government to take the observatory into state property. In 1899, the Hurbanovo site was renamed to Royal Konkoly-founded Astrophysical Observatory, and operated under the direction of Konkoly-Thege and Rad\u00f3 K\u00f6vesligethy, a renowned geophysicist of the time. The main scientific profile of the institute was the photometry of stars, the observation of the Sun, meteor counting, and providing time service for the government. In 1913, an order for a 60&nbsp;cm (24\") telescope was finalized with the German Heyde company, but with the start of [[World War I]], the telescope was never built.\n\nAfter the end of World War I, \u00d3gyalla became part of the newly formed [[Czechoslovak Republic (1918\u20131938)|Czechoslovak Republic]]. The government transferred the scientific equipment to Budapest before the newly formed border was shut down, and in 1921 allocated a new property in the [[Buda Hills|Buda hills]] just west to Budapest to build a new astronomical observatory. The new building, known as the Sv\u00e1bhegy observatory after a nearby hill, was finished by 1924, and the 6\" refractor and the re-ordered 60&nbsp;cm Heyde telescope were set up in new domes by 1928. Scientific work in the observatory focussed on the light variations of [[Variable star|pulsating stars]], the orbits of [[binary star]]s, and searching for [[asteroid]]s. Measurements were made with [[photographic plate]]s and wedge photometers.\n\nThe observatory survived [[World War II]] with minor damages. In late 1944, observations were put on hold, and the optical elements of the telescopes were removed to protect them from aerial bombings. Soviet troops occupied the buildings from December 1944 until February 1945, but the library and the photographic laboratories were spared. Observations were resumed by July 1945.\n\nAfter the communist takeover of Hungary in 1948, a new network of research institutes, independent from universities, was set up under the [[Hungarian Academy of Sciences]] (HAS). The observatory was renamed to the Astronomical Institute of the HAS, but retained the traditional name, Konkoly Observatory, in English correspondences. With the communist isolation of the country, international relations shifted from predominantly German and American to Soviet and [[Eastern Bloc|Eastern-bloc]] partnerships. However, the international recognition of then director [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Detre (astronomer)|L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Detre]] kept some connections to the West alive. During one of his visits to the Western bloc, Detre received an RCA 1P21 photomultiplier tube from American astronomer [[Harlow Shapley]]  to start photometric measurements at the observatory in 1948. He subsequently smuggled in to the country despite the strict trade restrictions at the time. In 1957, after the launch of Sputnik, multiple independent satellite observing and tracking stations were set up in the country at the suggestion of the Soviet Union. The institute provided coordination for these stations, and in 1966, the [[Baja, Hungary|Baja]] station merged into the institute.\n\nRelations with the West soon eased and at the 1961 General Assembly of the [[International Astronomical Union]] at Berkeley, the institute was tasked with setting up and circulating the ''Information Bulletin on Variable Stars''. The Bulletin was envisaged to be a rapid communications platform between variable star observers, but it later expanded into a peer-reviewed journal for short papers and notes about variable stars.\n\nThe institute expanded in the 1960-70s with the foundation and subsequent independence of the [[Debrecen Heliophysical Observatory]] and the installation of new telescopes at Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151 Mountain Station. In 1982, the observatories in Debrecen and Budapest were merged back together to form the Research Institute for Astronomy of the HAS. In 1992, the Baja station was separated from the institute and handed over to the county council of [[B\u00e1cs-Kiskun County|B\u00e1cs-Kiskun]].\n\nIn 2012, the Hungarian Academy of Sciences reorganized the structure of its institute network:<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nature.com/news/rhapsody-for-hungarian-science-1.9619|title=Rhapsody for Hungarian science|last=Schiermeier|first=Quirin|date=12 December 2011|work=Nature News}}</ref> the Astronomical Institute was merged with three other entities (Institutes for Geography, Geochemistry, and Geodesy and Geophysics) to form the Research Center for Astronomy and Earth Sciences.\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" widths=\"600\" heights=\"180\">\nFile:Konkoly-main-building.jpg|The main building of the observatory.\nFile:Konkoly domes.jpg|Telescope domes at Konkoly Observatory in Budapest. From left: the 6\", 7\" and 24\" domes. The latter houses the 60&nbsp;cm Heyde refractor.\n</gallery>\n\n=== Debrecen Heliophysical Observatory ===\n{{main|Debrecen Heliophysical Observatory}}\nIn 1946, a new Solar physics department was initiated under the leadership of L\u00f3r\u00e1nt Dezs\u0151. In 1958, the department moved to [[Debrecen]] to form a new solar observatory independent of the Astronomical Institute. Observations of the Sun started with two photoheliograph telescopes, one of which was relocated to the top of the water tower at [[Gyula, Hungary|Gyula]] in 1972. In 1973, a large [[coronagraph]] telescope with a 53&nbsp;cm aperture was set up, but observations were hindered by the cumbersome mechanical setup. Given the low elevation of the observatory of just 124 m above sea level, the coronagraph was only capable to observe the [[chromosphere]] of the Sun, not the [[corona]] itself.\n\nThe main scientific output of the observatory has been the detailed documentation of the [[Photosphere|photospheric]] activity of the Sun.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fenyi.solarobs.csfk.mta.hu/en/databases/Summary/|title=Summary table of databases at the Debrecen Observatory|last=Baranyi|first=T\u00fcnde}}</ref> The positions, sizes, structures of sunspots and sunspot groups are determined and recorded daily, to provide long-term, homogeneous observations of the Sun. The Debrecen Photoheliographic Data (DPD) database is the direct continuation of the [[Royal Observatory, Greenwich|Greenwich]] Photoheliographic Results that were collected between 1874-1976. Originally, analog [[Photographic plate|photographs]] and [[Charge-coupled device|CCD]] images were collected locally, or from partner observatories, but with the advent of reliable space-based observations, the work transitioned to the analysis of images from the [[Solar and Heliospheric Observatory|SOHO]] and [[Solar Dynamics Observatory|SDO]] spacecrafts. Further data products include the reanalysis of the Greenwich catalog, and older observations based on Hungarian drawings of the Sun.\n\nIn 1982, the observatory merged back into the Konkoly Astronomical Institute, and became a department of it once again. In 2015, the old observatory building in Debrecen was deemed unfeasible to maintain, and was closed down. The coronagraph was disassembled, and offices and personnel were transferred to the [[ATOMKI]] institute of the HAS in Debrecen. Given that space-based imagery has superseded the ground-based observations as the input source of the databases, the two photoheliographs were also decommissioned and removed from their mounts at Debrecen and Gyula.\n\n=== Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151 Mountain Station ===\n{{main|Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151 Station}}In 1951, the observatory secured funding for a new mapping telescope. The initial order was for a 0.9 m, f/3 Sonnefeld telescope but it was soon modified for a 60/90 com [[Schmidt camera|Schmidt telescope]]. With the light pollution of Budapest steadily increasing, a more remote location was sought for the telescope. After settling for Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151 peak in the [[M\u00e1tra|M\u00e1tra mountains]], about 80&nbsp;km away from the capital, a residence building was constructed in 1960, and the new Schmidt telescope was installed in 1962. The telescope provided a 10\u00b0x10\u00b0 field of view with photographic plates and could be equipped with an objective prism for low-resolution mass spectroscopic observations. The large field-of-view led to numerous supernova and asteroid discoveries at the time.\n\nIn 1966, a smaller, 0.5 m Cassegrain telescope with a two-channel photoelectric photometer was installed.\n\nFinally, a 1 m [[Ritchey\u2013Chr\u00e9tien telescope|Ritchey-Chr\u00e9tien]]-[[Coud\u00e9 telescope|coud\u00e9]] (RCC) telescope was installed in 1974, for high-resolution imaging and photometry of fainter targets. This marked the end of the initial development of Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151 station.[[File:Piszkesteto-observatory.jpg|alt=Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151 Mountain Station|thumb|300x300px|Aerial image of Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151 Mountain Station of the Konkoly Observatory in the M\u00e1tra hills.]]\n\nIn the late 1990s, photographic plates and photometers were replaced with CCD cameras on the Schmidt and RCC telescopes. In 2015, an echelle spectrograph with a spectral resolution of R=20,000 was installed on the RCC telescope.\n\nA 40&nbsp;cm Ritchey-Chr\u00e9tien telescope was set up in 2010, intended for automated remote observations. The telescope is currently under refurbishment.\n\nThe Fly's Eye system, consisting of 19 small cameras to observe the whole sky above 30\u00b0 altitude simultaneously, was installed in 2016.\n\nA new, automated 0.8 m telescope to track transient events, e.g., supernovae, is expected to be installed in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mta.hu/mta_hirei/szupernovak-gammakitoresek-fekete-lyukak-ket-komoly-robottavcso-epul-magyarorszagon-a-legizgalmasabb-csillagaszati-jelensegek-megfigyelesere-107372|title=Szupern\u00f3v\u00e1k, gammakit\u00f6r\u00e9sek, fekete lyukak: k\u00e9t komoly robott\u00e1vcs\u0151 \u00e9p\u00fcl Magyarorsz\u00e1gon a legizgalmasabb csillag\u00e1szati jelens\u00e9gek megfigyel\u00e9s\u00e9re|last=J\u00f3zsef|first=Vink\u00f3|date=7 February 2017|work=MTA H\u00edrek}}</ref>\n\nPiszk\u00e9stet\u0151 also hosts other instrumentations, including a [http://www.seismology.hu/index.php/en/home/live-seismograms seismic] and gravimetric station of the Institute for Geophysics and Geodesy, and an infrasound detector array.\n\n== Main research areas ==\n* Variable stars, stellar photometry, space-based photometry, exoplanets.\n* Astrochemistry, nuclear astrophysics, stellar dust. Includes the RADIOSTAR (Radioactivities from Stars to Solar Systems) [[European Research Council|ERC]] project.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mta.hu/mta_hirei/mi-volt-itt-a-naprendszer-elott-nyertes-erc-palyazat-az-mta-csfk-ban-107188|title=Mi volt itt a Naprendszer el\u0151tt? \u2013 Nyertes ERC-p\u00e1ly\u00e1zat az MTA CSFK-ban|date=5 December 2016|work=MTA H\u00edrek}}</ref>\n* Fly's Eye group: instrumentation and time-domain astronomy.\n* Small bodies in the Solar system: moons, TNOs, centaurs, comets, near-Earth asteroids, debris disks around other stars.\n* Protoplanetary disks and planet formation, star formation, infrared astronomy. Includes the SACCRED (Structured Accretion Disks) ERC project.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mta.hu/mta_hirei/harom-magyar-kutato-az-erc-starting-grant-idei-nyertesei-kozott-106775|title=Bolyg\u00f3keletkez\u00e9s, \u00fczemanyag f\u00fcstb\u0151l, tanul\u00e1s \u00e9s figyelem: h\u00e1rom magyar kutat\u00f3 az ERC Starting Grant 2016-os nyertesei k\u00f6z\u00f6tt|date=29 August 2016|work=MTA H\u00edrek}}</ref>\n* Solar and stellar activity, Doppler-imaging, differential rotation in stars, magnetic activity and dynamos, sunspot tracking.\n* Laboratory astrophysics and geochemistry, meteorites, planetary surfaces.\n* High-energy astrophysics, statistics of gamma-ray bursts.\n* Transient astrophysical objects (GINOP program).\n* Cosmic effects and risks (GINOP program).\n\n== Nomenclature ==\nThe observatory has had many different designations over the years. The current formal designation of the observatory is \"Konkoly Observatory, Research Centre for Astronomy and Earth Sciences, Hungarian Academy of Sciences\" ({{lang-hu|Magyar Tudom\u00e1nyos Akad\u00e9mia Csillag\u00e1szati \u00e9s F\u00f6ldtudom\u00e1nyi Kutat\u00f3k\u00f6zpontja, Konkoly Thege Mikl\u00f3s Csillag\u00e1szati Int\u00e9zet}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konkoly.hu/general.shtml|title=Konkoly Observatory of the Hungarian Academy of Sciences|website=www.konkoly.hu|accessdate=18 August 2017}}</ref> A former name, ''[http://svabhegyicsillagvizsgalo.hu/ Sv\u00e1bhegyi Csillagvizsg\u00e1l\u00f3]'', has been revived and used as branding for the public events and exhibitions hosted in the observatory and the 24\" inch dome in particular.\n\n== Publications ==\nThe observatory publishes multiple [http://konkoly.hu/publications_hun.shtml periodicals]. The most important one is the ''Information Bulletin on Variable Stars'', established by the [[International Astronomical Union|IAU]] in 1961 that contains peer-reviewed papers about variable star research and discoveries. Since 2011, IBVS is published as an online-only, [[Open access|open-access]], [[Article processing charge|APC]]-free journal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oastories.org/2011/09/hungary-journal-information-bulletin-on-variable-stars/|title=International Bulletin on Variable Stars: Fast, free and fifty: an open access star|date=September 2011|website=Open Access Success Stories}}</ref>\n\nLarger amounts of observational data and proceedings of meetings and conferences have been published in the ''Communications of the Konkoly Observatory'' (originally published under various Hungarian and German titles, like ''Mitteilungen der Sternwarte Budapest/Sv\u00e1bhegy,'' and later as ''Mitteilungen der Sternwarte der Ungarishen Akademie der Wissenshaften''). The observatory also published a few issues of ''Monographs'' (for History of Astronomy topics) and ''Occasional Technical Notes''.\n\n== Equipment ==\nCurrent equipment and locations:\n* 1 m RCC telescope (Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151). The main instrument, equipped with a medium-resolution echelle spectrograph and an EMCCD camera. \n* 60/90 Schmidt telescope (Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151). \n* 50&nbsp;cm Cassegrain telescope (Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151). Under renovation.\n* 40&nbsp;cm Ritchey-Cr\u00e9tien telescope (Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151). Under renovation.\n* [http://flyseye.net Fly's Eye] all-sky camera system (Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151).\n* 80&nbsp;cm telescope - under acquisition, to be installed at Piszk\u00e9stet\u0151.\n* [http://konkoly.hu/24 60 cm Heyde] Newton/Cassegrain telescope (Budapest). Decommissioned after 2013, it is being renovated for public demonstrations.\n* 7\" coud\u00e9 refractor (Budapest). Decommissioned.\n* coronagraph. Originally in Debrecen, decommissioned and disassembled.\n* 5\" photoheliograph (Debrecen). Decommissioned.\n* 6\" photoheliograph (Gyula). Decommissioned.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Open access in Hungary]] (publishing)\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.konkoly.hu/ Konkoly Observatory]\n* [http://www.konkoly.hu/staff/kollath/thefirst.html History of Konkoly]\n* [http://www.konkoly.hu/IBVS/IBVS.html Information Bulletin on Variable Stars]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Astronomical observatories in Hungary]]\n", "name_user": "Netoholic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDebrecen Heliophysical Observatory:post-move link fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Konkoly_Observatory"}
{"title_page": "European Canadians", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = European Canadians\n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| population = '''25,111,695'''<br>72.9% of the total Canadian population<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Geo2=&Code2=&SearchText=Canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1&type=0#fnb95-ref|title=Census Profile, 2016 Census - Canada [Country] and Canada [Country]|last=Government of Canada|first=Statistics Canada|date=2017-02-08|website=www12.statcan.gc.ca|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref> ([[Canada 2016 Census|2016 Census]])\n| regions = [[List of regions of Canada|All areas of Canada]]<br>less prevalent in the [[Northern Canada|North]]\n| region1 = \n| pop1 = \n| ref1 = \n| langs = Predominantly [[Canadian English|English]]{{\u2022}}[[Canadian French|French]]<br><small>Historically [[Canadian Gaelic|Scottish Gaelic]]{{\u2022}}[[Newfoundland Irish|Irish]] were spoken in certain regions</small>\n| rels = Predominantly [[Christianity in Canada|Christianity]] ([[Protestantism in Canada|Protestantism]] and [[Catholic Church in Canada|Roman Catholicism]]); Minority religions: [[Buddhism in Canada|Buddhism]], [[Judaism]], [[Islam in Canada|Islam]]\n| related = [[European diaspora]], [[European ethnic groups|Europeans]], [[European Americans]], [[European Australians]],   [[European New Zealanders]], [[British people|British]] ([[English people|English]], [[Scottish people|Scottish]], [[Welsh people|Welsh]], [[Ulster-Scots]]), [[Irish people|Irish]], [[French people|French]], [[German people|German]], [[Italians|Italian]], [[Dutch people|Dutch]], [[Ukrainian people|Ukrainian]], [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]]\n| footnotes = It includes people who aren't of aboriginal origin and didn't make part of a visible minority group.\"/>|\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\n'''European Canadians''' ({{lang-fr|les Canadiens Europ\u00e9ens}}), also known as '''Euro-Canadians''', are [[Canadians]] with ancestry from [[Europe]].<ref>[http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/euro-canadian www.oxforddictionaries.com] Euro-Canadian definition</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2018/09/11/eye-opening-show-tackles-white-canadians-racism-toward-indigenous-people_a_23522921/ |title=Eye-Opening Show, 'First Contact,' Tackles White Canadians' Racism Toward Indigenous People |last=Kappler |first=Maija |publisher=Huffington Post |quote=Example of White Canadian being used}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Stories from Home: First Nations, Land Claims, and Euro-Canadians |journal = American Ethnologist|volume = 21|issue = 4|pages = 776\u2013791|last=Menzies |first=Charles |publisher=American Anthropological Association |quote=Example of Euro-Canadian being used|jstor = 646839|year = 1994|doi = 10.1525/ae.1994.21.4.02a00060}}</ref> They form the largest [[Panethnicity|panethnic]] group within [[Canada]].\n\nThe [[French Canadians|French]] were the first Europeans to establish a continuous presence in what is now Canada. [[H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Desportes]] is considered the first white child born in [[New France]]. She was born circa 1620, to Pierre Desportes (born [[Lisieux]], [[Normandy|Normandie]], France) and Fran\u00e7oise Langlois.<ref name=\"DCBO\">{{cite DCB |last=Bennett |first=Ethel M. G. |title=Desportes, H\u00e9l\u00e8ne  |volume=1 |url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/desportes_helene_1E.html}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Canada 2016 Census|2016 census]], the largest European ancestry groups originated from the British Isles (11,211,850 including 6,320,085 [[English Canadians|English]], 4,799,005 [[Scottish Canadians|Scottish]] and 4,627,000 [[Irish Canadians|Irish]]), [[French Canadians|French]] (4,680,820), [[German Canadians|German]] (3,322,405), [[Italian Canadians|Italian]] (1,587,965).<ref name=\"Census Profile, 2016 Census\">[http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&Data=Count&SearchText=Canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Ethnic%20origin&TABID=1&wbdisable=true Census Profile, 2016 Census] - Ethnic origin population</ref> However, the country's largest [[Ethnic origins of people in Canada|self-reported ethnic origin]] is \"Canadian\" (accounting for 11,135,965 of the population). Since 1996, \"Canadian\" as an ethnic group has been added to census questionnaires for possible ancestry, which likely caused [[English Canadians]], [[Canadians of English descent|British Canadians]] and [[French Canadians]] to become severely underrepresented. The grouping is similar to that of \"''[[American ethnicity|American]]''\" in neighbouring United States and is most commonly espoused by European Canadians whose ancestors have been some of the earliest European settlers of what is now Canada, to the point where they no longer feel a connection to their countries of origin.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CofPBh5BRhwC&pg=PA313 The Changing Face of Canada: Essential Readings in Population]</ref> In the 2011 National Household Survey Profile, 10,563,805 people (32.1%) chose \"Canadian\" as their ethnic group, making it the single largest group in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Data=Count&SearchText=Canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&A1=All&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1|title=National Household Survey Profile|publisher=Statistics Canada|year=2011|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Number of European Canadians==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#efefef;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#efefef;\" | Population\n! style=\"background:#efefef;\" | % of Canadian<br>population \n! style=\"background:#efefef;\" | {{abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n| 1871||3,433,315 ||98.5||<ref name=\"Ethnic origins\">{{cite web|url=https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/pub/11-516-x/pdf/5500092-eng.pdf|title=Ethnic origins: Census of Canada (Page: 17)|accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"justice.gc.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.justice.gc.ca/eng/rp-pr/csj-sjc/jsp-sjp/rp02_8-dr02_8/rp02_8.pdf|title=Table 1: Population by Ethnic Origin, Canada 1921-1971 (P.2)|website=justice.gc.ca|accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=YearBook>{{cite web|format=PDF|url=https://archive.org/details/canadbook19222300casouoft|title=Canada Year Book 1922-23: Racial Origin|publisher=Census and Statistics Office of Canada|date=1921|pages=158\u201359}}</ref> \n|-\n| 1881||4,146,900 ||95.9 ||<ref name=\"nber.org\">[https://www.nber.org/chapters/c5105.pdf Canada - Origins according to the censuses]. 1871, 1881, 1901, 1911 AND 1921. (Page: 134-135)</ref><ref name=YearBook/> \n|-\n| 1901||5,170,522 ||96.0||<ref name=\"nber.org\">[https://www.nber.org/chapters/c5105.pdf Canada - Origins according to the censuses]. 1871, 1881, 1901, 1911 AND 1921. (Page: 134-135)</ref><ref name=YearBook/> \n|-\n| 1911||7,005,583 ||94.35||<ref name=\"nber.org\">[https://www.nber.org/chapters/c5105.pdf Canada - Origins according to the censuses]. 1871, 1881, 1901, 1911 AND 1921. (Page: 134-135)</ref><ref name=YearBook/> \n|-\n| 1921||8,568,584 ||96.0||<ref name=\"nber.org\">[https://www.nber.org/chapters/c5105.pdf Canada - Origins according to the censuses]. 1871, 1881, 1901, 1911 AND 1921. (Page: 134-135)</ref><ref name=YearBook/> \n|-\n| 1931||10,134,313 ||97.7 ||<ref name=\"Ethnic origins\"/><ref name=YearBook/> \n|-\n| 1941||11,242,868 ||97.8||<ref name=\"Ethnic origins\"/><ref name=\"justice.gc.ca\"/> \n|-\n| 1951||13,582,574 ||96.83||<ref name=\"Ethnic origins\"/><ref name=\"justice.gc.ca\"/> \n|-\n| 1961||17,653,864 ||96.8||<ref name=\"Ethnic origins\"/><ref name=\"justice.gc.ca\"/> \n|-\n| 1966|| - ||96.8 ||<ref name=\"Ethnic origins\"/><ref name=\"justice.gc.ca\"/> \n|-\n|1971\n|20,763,915\n|96.3\n|<ref name=\