Profile\".] Statistics Canada. 2011. A total of 25,186,890 persons didn't make part of a visible minority or didn't state an aboriginal origin.</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|25,111,695\n|72.9\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Geo2=&Code2=&SearchText=Canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1&type=0#fnb95-ref|title=Census Profile, 2016 Census - Canada [Country] and Canada [Country]|last=Government of Canada|first=Statistics Canada|date=2017-02-08|website=www12.statcan.gc.ca|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\nThe table shows the European-Canadian population per census beginning with the [[Canada 1871 Census|1871 Census]] were it reached a peak of 98.5 percent, however, their proportion of the total Canadian population has been decreasing gradually since the mid-twentieth century to the most recent census in 2016. Canada enumerated its population by race between 1871 and 1971 and ethnic origins.\n\n===Present===\nCanadians who self-identified with European origins are still the largest ethnic group in Canada with 72.9% or 25,111,695 persons who didn't make part of a visible minority or didn't state an aboriginal origin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Geo2=&Code2=&SearchText=Canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1&type=0#fnb95-ref|title=Census Profile, 2016 Census - Canada [Country] and Canada [Country]|last=Government of Canada|first=Statistics Canada|date=2017-02-08|website=www12.statcan.gc.ca|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> A decrease since 1971 (45 years) where 96.3% of the population identified as European.<ref name=\"justice.gc.ca\" /><ref name=\"Ethnic origins\">{{cite web|url=https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/pub/11-516-x/pdf/5500092-eng.pdf|title=Ethnic origins: Census of Canada (Page: 17)|accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\nElements of Aboriginal, French, British and more recent immigrant customs, languages and religions have combined to form the [[culture of Canada]] and thus a [[Canadian identity]]. Canada has also been strongly influenced by its linguistic, geographic and economic neighbour, the [[United States]].\n\nThe top ten cities as per population of European Canadians (not members of a visible minority and no Aboriginal status) are as follows (2016 Census):\n# Toronto 1,282,750\n# Montreal 1,082,615\n# Calgary 744,625\n# Ottawa 652,650\n# Edmonton 524,265\n# Quebec City 475,720\n# Hamilton 415,740\n# Winnipeg 412,645\n# Halifax 336,375\n# Mississauga 302,375\nThe top ten such Census Metropolitan Areas (CMAs) are as follows:\n# Montreal 3,070,210\n# Toronto 2,804,630\n# Vancouver 1,179,100\n# Ottawa - Gatineau 981,630\n# Calgary 869,555\n# Edmonton 857,085\n# Quebec City 729,310\n# Hamilton 590,310\n# Winnipeg 473,360\n# Kitchener - Cambridge - Waterloo 407,460\n\n==Culture==\n{{Main|Canadian culture|Western culture}}\n[[File:MoWestCanadaDay.JPG|245px|thumb|right|European Canadians celebrating [[Canada Day]].]]\n\nThe culture of the Canadians of European descent, European-Canadian culture, is the main [[culture of Canada]]. From their earliest presence in [[North America]], European Canadians have contributed [[literature]], [[art]], [[architecture]], [[Film|cinema]] and [[theater]], [[religion]] and [[philosophy]], [[ethics]], [[Agriculture|agricultural]] skills, [[food]]s, [[medicine]], [[science]] and [[technology]], [[fashion]] and [[clothing]] styles, [[music]], [[language]], [[business]], [[economics]], [[legal system]], [[political system]], and social and technological innovation to [[Canadian culture]]. European-Canadian culture derived its earliest influences from English, French, Scottish, Welsh, and Irish settlers and is quantitatively the largest proportion of Canadian culture. The overall Canadian culture reflects European-Canadian culture, also known as White Canadian culture. The culture has been developing since long before Canada formed a separate country. Much of Canadian culture shows influences from English culture, with later periphery influence, due to 19th-century immigration, from different regions of Europe, such as the customs of [[Eastern European Canadians]]. Colonial ties to Great Britain spread the [[English language]], legal system and other cultural attributes.\n\n===Canadian flag===\n[[File:Ruth & George Stanley.jpg|thumb|right|175px|[[George Stanley]] designer of the current [[Canadian flag]].]]\n*'''[[Canadian flag]]''' - In 1964, Prime Minister [[Lester B. Pearson]] formed a committee to resolve the issue, sparking a serious [[Great Canadian Flag Debate|debate about a flag change]] to replace the [[Union Flag]]. Out of three choices, the maple leaf design by [[George Stanley]],<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/the-stanley-flag/|first=Richard|last=Foot|title=The Stanley Flag|encyclopedia=The Canadian Encyclopedia |publisher=Historica Canada|date=February 13, 2014|edition=online}}</ref> based on the flag of the [[Royal Military College of Canada]], was selected. The flag made its first official appearance on February 15, 1965.\n\n===Music===\n[[File:Robert Stanley Weir 1899.png|175px|thumb|right|[[Scottish-Canadian]] [[Robert Stanley Weir]] wrote the lyrics to ''[[O Canada]]''.]]\nAnother area of cultural influence are [[Anthems and nationalistic songs of Canada|Canadian Patriotic songs]]:\n*'''[[O Canada|Canadian National Anthem]]''' - Two Canadians of French descent [[Adolphe-Basile Routhier]] wrote the lyrics and [[Calixa Lavall\u00e9e]] composed the music in 1880.<ref name=\"canada\">{{cite encyclopedia|first=Andrew|last=McIntosh|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/en/article/o-canada/|title=O Canada|encyclopedia=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]|date=March 26, 2012|accessdate=May 26, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"anthem-fr\">{{cite web|title=Hymne national du Canada|work=Canadian Heritage|publisher=Government of Canada|date=June 23, 2008|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/symbl/anthem-fra.cfm|accessdate=June 26, 2008}}</ref> The English lyrics which is the official and most popular version were written in 1908 by [[Scottish-Canadian]] [[Robert Stanley Weir]].<ref name=DCHOCanada>{{cite web| url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/symbl/anthem-eng.cfm| last=Department of Canadian Heritage| authorlink=Department of Canadian Heritage| title=Canadian Heritage \u2013 National Anthem: O Canada| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=June 29, 2010}}</ref>\n*'''[[The Maple Leaf Forever]]''' - is an older but ''unofficial national'' anthem written by Scotsman [[Alexander Muir]] in 1867.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ducimus.com/Marches.htm|title=Marches|publisher=L'Association Canadienne De L'Infanterie/Canadian Infantry Association|accessdate=May 4, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422081237/http://www.ducimus.com/Marches.htm|archivedate=April 22, 2012|df=mdy}}</ref> It was in consideration for official national anthem, however, as no French version was ever written, it was never popular with Francophones.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/symbl/patriot-eng.cfm |title=Canadian Heritage \u2013 Patriotic Songs |publisher=Pch.gc.ca |date=March 3, 2010 |accessdate=October 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Sport===\n*'''[[Ice Hockey]]''' - British soldiers and immigrants to Canada and the United States brought their stick-and-ball games with them and played them on the ice and snow of winter. Ice hockey was first played in Canada during the early nineteenth century, based on similar sports such as [[field hockey]] that were played in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olympic.org/ice-hockey-equipment-and-history?tab=history|title=Ice Hockey Equipment and History|publisher=The Olympic Movement|accessdate=January 3, 2012}}</ref> The sport was originally played with a stick and ball, but in 1860 a group of English veterans from the [[Royal Canadian Rifle Regiment]] played a game in [[Kingston, Ontario]], utilising a [[Hockey puck|puck]] for what is believed to be the first time. This match, played on the frozen harbour by the city, is sometimes considered to be the birth of modern ice hockey.<ref name=\"ihuk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.icehockeyuk.co.uk/about-ice-hockey-s12744 |title=About Ice Hockey|publisher=[[Ice Hockey UK]]|accessdate=December 27, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214091604/http://www.icehockeyuk.co.uk/about-ice-hockey-s12744|archivedate=February 14, 2012|df=mdy}}</ref>\n\n==European ethnic origins table==\n{|class=\"sort wikitable sortable\" font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n!Origins||[[Canada 1871 Census|1871]]{{ref|1|1}} ||% ||[[Canada 1951 Census|1951]]{{ref|3|3}} ||% ||2006||% ||2011{{ref|4|4}} ||% ||Change 2006-2011<br>\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Albania}} [[Albanian Canadian|Albanian]]\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|22,395\n| -\n|28,270\n| -\n| -\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Austria}} [[Austrian Canadian|Austrian]]\n| -\n| -\n|32,231\n| -\n|194,255\n| -\n|197,990\n| -\n| -\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Belgium}} [[Belgian Canadian|Belgian]]\n| -\n| -\n|35,148\n| -\n|168,910\n| -\n|176,615\n| -\n| -\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Bosnia}} [[Bosnian Canadian|Bosnian]]\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|21,045\n|\n|22,920\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{flagicon|UK}} British Isles\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|403,915\n|\n|576,030\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{flagicon|UK}} Other British\n|7,773\n|0.2%\n|92,236\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Bulgaria}} [[Bulgarian Canadian|Bulgarian]]\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|27,255\n|\n|30,485\n|\n| \n|-\n|{{flagicon|Canada}} [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|10,066,290\n|32.22%\n|10,563,805\n|32.1%\n| \n|-\n|{{flagicon|Croatia}} [[Croatian Canadian|Croatian]]\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|110,880\n|\n|114,880\n|\n| \n|-\n|{{flagicon|Czech Republic}} [[Czech Canadian|Czech]]\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|98,090\n|\n|94,805\n|\n| \n|-\n|{{flagicon|Czechoslovakia}} Czech and Slovak\n| -\n| -\n|63,959\n|\n