etails/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Geo2=&Code2=&SearchText=Canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1&type=0#fnb95-ref|title=Census Profile, 2016 Census - Canada [Country] and Canada [Country]|last=Government of Canada|first=Statistics Canada|date=2017-02-08|website=www12.statcan.gc.ca|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref> ([[Canada 2016 Census|2016 Census]])\n| regions = [[List of regions of Canada|All areas of Canada]]<br>less prevalent in the [[Northern Canada|North]]\n| region1 = \n| pop1 = \n| ref1 = \n| langs = Predominantly [[Canadian English|English]]{{\u2022}}[[Canadian French|French]]<br><small>Historically [[Canadian Gaelic|Scottish Gaelic]]{{\u2022}}[[Newfoundland Irish|Irish]] were spoken in certain regions</small>\n| rels = Predominantly [[Christianity in Canada|Christianity]] ([[Protestantism in Canada|Protestantism]] and [[Catholic Church in Canada|Roman Catholicism]]); Minority religions: [[Buddhism in Canada|Buddhism]], [[Judaism]], [[Islam in Canada|Islam]]\n| related = [[European diaspora]], [[European ethnic groups|Europeans]], [[European Americans]], [[European Australians]],   [[European New Zealanders]], [[British people|British]] ([[English people|English]], [[Scottish people|Scottish]], [[Welsh people|Welsh]], [[Ulster-Scots]]), [[Irish people|Irish]], [[French people|French]], [[German people|German]], [[Italians|Italian]], [[Dutch people|Dutch]], [[Ukrainian people|Ukrainian]], [[Polish people|Polish]], [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]]\n| footnotes = It includes people who aren't of aboriginal origin and didn't make part of a visible minority group.\"/>|\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\n'''European Canadians''' ({{lang-fr|les Canadiens Europ\u00e9ens}}), also known as '''Euro-Canadians''', are [[Canadians]] with ancestry from [[Europe]].<ref>[http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/euro-canadian www.oxforddictionaries.com] Euro-Canadian definition</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2018/09/11/eye-opening-show-tackles-white-canadians-racism-toward-indigenous-people_a_23522921/ |title=Eye-Opening Show, 'First Contact,' Tackles White Canadians' Racism Toward Indigenous People |last=Kappler |first=Maija |publisher=Huffington Post |quote=Example of White Canadian being used}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Stories from Home: First Nations, Land Claims, and Euro-Canadians |journal = American Ethnologist|volume = 21|issue = 4|pages = 776\u2013791|last=Menzies |first=Charles |publisher=American Anthropological Association |quote=Example of Euro-Canadian being used|jstor = 646839|year = 1994|doi = 10.1525/ae.1994.21.4.02a00060}}</ref> They form the largest [[Panethnicity|panethnic]] group within [[Canada]].\n\nThe [[French Canadians|French]] were the first Europeans to establish a continuous presence in what is now Canada. [[H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Desportes]] is considered the first white child born in [[New France]]. She was born circa 1620, to Pierre Desportes (born [[Lisieux]], [[Normandy|Normandie]], France) and Fran\u00e7oise Langlois.<ref name=\"DCBO\">{{cite DCB |last=Bennett |first=Ethel M. G. |title=Desportes, H\u00e9l\u00e8ne  |volume=1 |url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/desportes_helene_1E.html}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Canada 2016 Census|2016 census]], the largest European ancestry groups originated from the British Isles (11,211,850 including 6,320,085 [[English Canadians|English]], 4,799,005 [[Scottish Canadians|Scottish]] and 4,627,000 [[Irish Canadians|Irish]]), [[French Canadians|French]] (4,680,820), [[German Canadians|German]] (3,322,405), [[Italian Canadians|Italian]] (1,587,965).<ref name=\"Census Profile, 2016 Census\">[http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Geo2=PR&Code2=01&Data=Count&SearchText=Canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Ethnic%20origin&TABID=1&wbdisable=true Census Profile, 2016 Census] - Ethnic origin population</ref> However, the country's largest [[Ethnic origins of people in Canada|self-reported ethnic origin]] is \"Canadian\" (accounting for 11,135,965 of the population). Since 1996, \"Canadian\" as an ethnic group has been added to census questionnaires for possible ancestry, which likely caused [[English Canadians]], [[Canadians of English descent|British Canadians]] and [[French Canadians]] to become severely underrepresented. The grouping is similar to that of \"''[[American ethnicity|American]]''\" in neighbouring United States and is most commonly espoused by European Canadians whose ancestors have been some of the earliest European settlers of what is now Canada, to the point where they no longer feel a connection to their countries of origin.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CofPBh5BRhwC&pg=PA313 The Changing Face of Canada: Essential Readings in Population]</ref> In the 2011 National Household Survey Profile, 10,563,805 people (32.1%) chose \"Canadian\" as their ethnic group, making it the single largest group in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Data=Count&SearchText=Canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&A1=All&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1|title=National Household Survey Profile|publisher=Statistics Canada|year=2011|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Number of European Canadians==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#efefef;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#efefef;\" | Population\n! style=\"background:#efefef;\" | % of Canadian<br>population \n! style=\"background:#efefef;\" | {{abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n| 1871||3,433,315 ||98.5||<ref name=\"Ethnic origins\">{{cite web|url=https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/pub/11-516-x/pdf/5500092-eng.pdf|title=Ethnic origins: Census of Canada (Page: 17)|accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"justice.gc.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.justice.gc.ca/eng/rp-pr/csj-sjc/jsp-sjp/rp02_8-dr02_8/rp02_8.pdf|title=Table 