a}} [[Yugoslav Canadian|Yugoslav]]\n| -\n| -\n|21,404\n|\n|65,305\n|\n|48,320\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Europe}} Other European\n| 3,791\n| 0.0%\n|35,616\n|\n|35,795\n|\n|48,760\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{flagicon|UK}} ''Total British''\n|2,110,502\n|60.6%\n|6,709,685\n|47.89%\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|- class=\"sortbottom\" style=\"background:lightgrey;\"\n|{{flagicon|Canada}} '''Canada'''\n|align = right|'''3,433,315'''\n|align = right|'''98.49%'''\n|align = right|'''13,582,574'''\n|align = right|'''96.83%'''\n|align = right|\n|align = right|\n|align = right|'''20,157,965'''{{ref|4|4}}\n|align = right| <small>'''N/A'''</small>\n|align = right|\n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" style=\"text-align:left;\"|<small>{{note|1|1}}</small> <small> First census of the Canadian federation.<ref name=\"nber.org\"/> The figures for 1871 are for the four original provinces only.</small> <br><small>{{note|2|2}}</small> <small>Includes Danish, Icelandic, Norwegian and Swedish.{{note|3|3}}</small> <small>Canada 1951 Census</small><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=zakCX5XPnAAC&pg=PA73&lpg=PA73&dq=2,110,502+census&source=bl&ots=vNC_XAhShE&sig=tqMUVz4v_WhFc4k9P8mAJEKFAhA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyrYqZs_DLAhVCXBQKHRr4CbcQ6AEIPzAJ#v=onepage&q=2%2C110%2C502%20census&f=false Multiculturalism and Immigration in Canada: An Introductory Reader] By Elspeth Cameron (Page: 73-73)</ref><ref>[http://www65.statcan.gc.ca/acyb02/1967/acyb02_19670197014-eng.htm Statistics Canada] Distribution of the population, by ethnic group, census years 1941, 1951 and 1961</ref><small>[[2006 Canada Census]]</small><ref name=\"www12.statcan.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.ca/english/census06/data/highlights/ethnic/pages/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo=PR&Code=01&Data=Count&Table=2&StartRec=1&Sort=3&Display=All&CSDFilter=5000|title=Ethnocultural Portrait of Canada - Data table|publisher=2.statcan.ca|date=October 6, 2010|accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref><br><small>{{note|4|4}}[[Canada 2011 Census]] National Household Survey: Data tables</small><ref>[http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/dt-td/Rp-eng.cfm?LANG=E&APATH=3&DETAIL=0&DIM=0&FL=A&FREE=0&GC=0&GID=0&GK=0&GRP=0&PID=105396&PRID=0&PTYPE=105277&S=0&SHOWALL=0&SUB=0&Temporal=2013&THEME=95&VID=0&VNAMEE=&VNAMEF 2011 National Household Survey: Data tables]</ref> <small>An extra 32% or 10,563,805 people identified as \"Canadian\" as their ethnic group, many <br>are of European origins.</small>\n|}\n\n==Prime Ministers==\nMost of the heritage that all twenty-three [[Prime Minister of Canada|Canadian Prime Minister]]s come from (or in some combination thereof): is [[British people|British]] ([[English people|English]], [[Scottish people|Scottish]], [[Ulster Scots people|Ulster Scot]] or [[Welsh people|Welsh]]) ancestry. Later Canadian Prime Ministers' ancestry can often be traced to ancestors from multiple nations in [[Europe]].\n{{col-begin}}{{col-2}}\n:1st    [[John A. Macdonald]] (Scottish)\n:2nd    [[Alexander Mackenzie (politician)|Alexander Mackenzie]] (Scottish)\n:3rd    [[John Abbott]] (English)\n:4th    [[John Sparrow David Thompson|John Thompson]] (Irish)\n:5th    [[Mackenzie Bowell]] (English)\n:6th    [[Charles Tupper]] (English)\n:7th    [[Wilfrid Laurier]] (French)\n:8th    [[Robert Borden]] (English)\n:9th    [[Arthur Meighen]] (Scotch-Irish)\n:10th   [[William Lyon Mackenzie King]] (Scottish)\n:11th   [[R. B. Bennett]] (English, Irish)\n:12th   [[Louis St. Laurent]] (French, Irish)\n{{col-break}}\n:13th   [[John Diefenbaker]] (German, Scottish)\n:14th   [[Lester B. Pearson]] (Anglo-Irish)\n:15th   [[Pierre Trudeau]] (French, Scottish)\n:16th   [[Joe Clark]] (Scottish, Irish)\n:17th   [[John Turner]] (English)\n:18th   [[Brian Mulroney]] (Irish)\n:19th   [[Kim Campbell]] (Scottish)\n:20th   [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]] (French)\n:21st   [[Paul Martin]] (Irish, French, Scottish)\n:22nd   [[Stephen Harper]] (English, Scottish)\n:23rd   [[Justin Trudeau]] (French, Scottish, English)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada|Europe}}\n* [[European diaspora]]\n* [[M\u00e9tis people (Canada)]]\n* [[Ethnic origins of people in Canada]]\n* [[Eastern European Canadians]]\n* [[European Americans]]\n* [[Demographics of Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|author1=Bramadat, Paul|author2=David Seljak|title=Religion and Ethnicity in Canada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VymssyK1Hs0C&pg=PA112|year=2009|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=9781442610187}}\n* {{cite book|author1=Bramadat, Paul|author2=David Seljak|title=Christianity and Ethnicity in Canada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z4HzXN4HQkQC&pg=PA247|year=2008|publisher=U of Toronto Press|page=247|isbn=9780802095848}}\n*{{cite book|last= Haig-Brown|first=C.|author2=Nock, D.A.|title=With Good Intentions: Euro-Canadian and Aboriginal Relations in Colonial Canada|publisher=UBC Press|year=2006|isbn=978-0-7748-1138-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vxFzgKZ0LKoC&dq=euro-canadian&printsec=frontcover}}\n* {{cite book|author=Kallen, Evelyn|title=Ethnicity and Human Rights in Canada: A Human Rights Perspective on Ethnicity, Racism, and Systemic Inequality|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xkqFAAAAMAAJ|year=2003|publisher=Oxford UP|isbn=9780195417425}}\n* Kralt, John. \"[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_hb039/is_1_35/ai_n29045486/?tag=content;col1 Country of Birth of Parents And Ethnic Origins]  - A Comparison of Reporting Patterns in the 2001 Census,\"\n*{{cite book\n|first = Paul R| last = Magocsi\n|authorlink =\n|title =Encyclopedia of Canada's peoples\n|edition =\n|publisher =Society of Ontario, University of Toronto Press\n|location =\n|year =1999\n|isbn =978-0-8020-2938-6\n|url =https://books.google.com/books?id=dbUuX0mnvQMC&lpg=PA582&dq=Territorial%20evolution%20of%20Canada&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=true\n }}; 1300pp; comprehensive scholarly coverage of every group\n\n* McLean, Lorna R. \"Education, identity, and citizenship in early modern Canada.\" ''Journal of Canadian Studies/Revue d'\u00e9tudes canadiennes'' 41.1 (2007): 5-30.\n* {{Cite book\n |first=Philip |last=Resnick\n |title=The European Roots Of Canadian Identity\n |publisher=Broadview Press\n |location=Peterborough, Ont.\n |isbn=978-1-55111-705-8\n |year=2005\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JJLOERVCUg0C&lpg=PP1&dq=The%20European%20Roots%20Of%20Canadian%20Identity&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=true\n }}\n* {{cite book|author=Yedlin, Tova|title=Central and East European Ethnicity in Canada: Adaptation and Preservation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K4Z8AAAACAAJ|year=1985|publisher=Central and East European Studies Society of Alberta|isbn=9780888649539}}\n\n===Statistical===\n* {{Cite book\n|last = Statistics Canada\n|title = Canada Year Book (CYB) annual 1867-1967\n|publisher = Federal Publications (Queen of Canada)\n|location = Ottawa\n|year= 2008\n|id =\n|url=http://www65.statcan.gc.ca/acyb_r000-eng.htm\n }}\n* {{Cite book\n|last = Statistics Canada\n|title = Canada Year Book\n|publisher = Federal Publications (Queen of Canada)\n|location = Ottawa\n|date= October 27, 2010\n|id =Catalogue no 11-402-XPE\n|url=http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/11-402-x/11-402-x2010000-eng.htm\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{People of Canada}}\n{{White people}}\n\n[[Category:Canadian people of European descent| ]]\n[[Category:European Canadian| ]]\n[[Category:European diaspora in North America]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "192.235.254.105", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_Canadians"}
{"title_page": "Alpha Trianguli Australis", "text_new": "{{Starbox begin\n| name = \u03b1 Trianguli Australis<br>(Atria)\n}}\n{{Starbox image\n| image =\n     <div style=\"position: relative\">[[File:Triangulum Australe IAU.svg|250px|alt=Diagram showing star positions and boundaries of the Triangulum Australe constellation and its surroundings]]\n     <div style=\"position: absolute; left: 93px; top: 128px\">[[File:Cercle rouge 100%.svg|12px]]</div>\n     </div>\n| caption=Location of \u03b1 Trianguli Australis (circled)\n}}\n{{Starbox observe\n| epoch    = J2000\n| ra       = {{RA|16|48|39.89508}}<ref name=aaa474_2_653/>\n| dec      = {{DEC|\u201369|01|39.7626}}<ref name=aaa474_2_653/>\n| appmag_v = 1.91<ref name=scfs/>\n| constell = [[Triangulum Australe]]\n}}\n{{Starbox character\n| class    = K2&nbsp;IIb-IIIa<ref name=aaa120_1_21/>\n| b-v      = +1.44<ref name=clpl4_99/>\n| u-b      = +1.56<ref name=clpl4_99/>\n| variable =\n}}\n{{Starbox astrometry\n| radial_v    = \u20133.3<ref name=scfs/>\n| prop_mo_ra  = 17.99<ref name=aaa474_2_653/>\n| prop_mo_dec = \u201331.58<ref name=aaa474_2_653/>\n| parallax    = 8.35\n| p_error     = 0.15\n| parallax_footnote = <ref name=aaa474_2_653/>\n| absmag_v    = \u20133.68<ref name=apj658_2_L107/>\n}}\n{{Starbox detail\n| mass     = 7<ref name=aaa120_1_21/>\n| radius   =\n| luminosity  = 5,500<ref name=apj658_2_L107/>\n| gravity  = 1.5<ref name=aaa120_1_21/>\n| temperature = 4,150<ref name=aaa120_1_21/>\n| metal_fe = \u20130.06<ref name=aaa120_1_21/>\n| rotational_velocity =\n| age      = {{nowrap|4.8 \u00d7 10<sup>7</sup>}}<ref name=aaa120_1_21/>\n}}\n{{Starbox catalog\n| names=Atria, [[Harvard Revised catalogue|HR]] 6217,  [[Cordoba Durchmusterung|CD]] \u221268\u00b02822, [[Henry Draper catalogue|HD]] 150798, [[Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory Star Catalog|SAO]] 253700, [[Fifth Fundamental Catalogue|FK5]] 625, GC 22558, [[Hipparcos catalogue|HIP]] 82273.<ref name=SIMBAD/>\n}}\n{{Starbox reference\n| Simbad=Alpha+Trianguli+Australis\n}}\n{{Starbox end}}\n\n'''Alpha Trianguli Australis''' ([[Latinisation of names|Latinised]] from '''\u03b1 Trianguli Australis''', abbreviated '''Alpha TrA''', '''\u03b1 TrA'''), officially named '''Atria''' {{IPAc-en|'|ei|t|r|i|@}},<ref name=Kunitzsch>{{cite book\n  |last=Kunitzsch |first=Paul\n  |last2=Smart |first2=Tim\n  |date = 2006  |edition = 2nd rev.\n  |title = A Dictionary of Modern star Names: A Short Guide to 254 Star Names and Their Derivations\n  |publisher = Sky Pub |location = Cambridge, Massachusetts\n  |isbn = 978-1-931559-44-7\n}}</ref><ref name=\"IAU-CSN\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pas.rochester.edu/~emamajek/WGSN/IAU-CSN.txt | title=IAU Catalog of Star Names |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref> is the brightest [[star]] in the southern [[constellation]] of [[Triangulum Australe]], forming an apex of a triangle with [[Beta Trianguli Australis]] and [[Gamma Trianguli Australis]] that gives the constellation its name ([[Latin]] for southern triangle).\n\n==Nomenclature==\n\n''\u03b1 Trianguli Australis'' (Latinised to ''Alpha Trianguli Australis'') is the star's [[Bayer designation]]. The historical name ''Atria'' is a contraction.<ref name=ridpath1989/><ref name=\"kaleratria\">{{cite web|url=http://stars.astro.illinois.edu/sow/atria.html|title=Atria (Alpha Trianguli Australis) |last=Kaler|first=Jim|work=Stars|publisher=[[University of Illinois]]|accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref> In 2016, the [[International Astronomical Union]] organized a [[IAU Working Group on Star Names|Working Group on Star Names]] (WGSN)<ref name=\"WGSN\">{{cite web | url=https://www.iau.org/science/scientific_bodies/working_groups/280/ | title=IAU Working Group on Star Names (WGSN)|accessdate=22 May 2016}}</ref> to catalog and standardize proper names for stars. The WGSN's first bulletin of July 2016<ref name=\"WGSN1\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pas.rochester.edu/~emamajek/WGSN/WGSN_bulletin1.pdf | title=Bulletin of the IAU Working Group on Star Names, No. 1 |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref> included a table of the first two batches of names approved by the WGSN; which included ''Atria'' for this star.\n\nIn [[Chinese language|Chinese]] caused by adaptation of the European southern hemisphere constellations into the Chinese system, {{lang|zh|\u4e09\u89d2\u5f62}} ({{lang|zh-Latn|S\u0101n Ji\u01ceo X\u00edng}}), meaning ''[[Chinese constellations#The Southern Asterisms|Triangle]]'', refers to an asterism consisting of \u03b1 Trianguli Australis, \u03b2 Trianguli Australis and \u03b3 Trianguli Australis. Consequently, \u03b1 Trianguli Australis itself is known as {{lang|zh|\u4e09\u89d2\u5f62\u4e09}} ({{lang|zh-Latn|S\u0101n Ji\u01ceo X\u00edng s\u0101n}}, {{lang-en|the Third Star of Triangle}}.)<ref>{{in lang|zh}} [http://aeea.nmns.edu.tw/2006/0607/ap060729.html AEEA (Activities of Exhibition and Education in Astronomy) \u5929\u6587\u6559\u80b2\u8cc7\u8a0a\u7db2 2006 \u5e74 7 \u6708 29 \u65e5]</ref>\n\n==Physical characteristics==\n\nAlpha Trianguli Australis is a [[bright giant]] star with an [[apparent magnitude]] of +1.91. Based upon [[parallax]] measurements, this star is located roughly {{Convert|391|ly|pc|abbr=off|lk=on}} distant from the Earth.<ref name=aaa474_2_653/> The estimated age of the star is 48 million years old; sufficiently old for a massive star to evolve away from the [[main sequence]] and expand into a giant.<ref name=aaa120_1_21/> It has a mass roughly seven times the [[solar mass|mass of the Sun]], but is emitting about 5,500 times the [[solar luminosity|Sun's luminosity]]. The [[effective temperature]] of the star's outer envelope is 4,150&nbsp;K,<ref name=aaa120_1_21/> which gives it the characteristic orange hue of a K-type star.<ref name=csiro/> With a diameter 130 times [[Solar radius|that of the Sun]], it would almost reach the orbit of [[Venus]] if placed at the centre of the [[Solar System]].\n\nThere is evidence that Atria may be a [[binary star]]. It displays unusual properties for a star of its class, including [[flare star|stellar flares]] and a higher than normal emission of X-rays. These can be explained by a young, [[Stellar magnetic field|magnetically active]] companion with a [[stellar classification]] of about G0&nbsp;V. Such a star would have a mass similar to the Sun, with an orbital period of at least 130&nbsp;years. Young, [[G-type star]]s have a high temperature [[stellar corona|corona]] and frequently emit flares causing sudden increases in luminosity. The pair may be separated by about 50&nbsp;[[astronomical unit]]s.<ref name=apj658_2_L107/>\n\n==In culture==\nAtria appears on the [[flag of Brazil]], symbolizing the state of [[Rio Grande do Sul]].<ref name=brazil_flag/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=aaa474_2_653>{{cite journal | first=F. | last=van Leeuwen |date=November 2007 | title=Validation of the new Hipparcos reduction | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=474 | issue=2 | pages=653\u2013664 | bibcode=2007A&A...474..653V | doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20078357 |arxiv = 0708.1752 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=aaa120_1_21>{{citation | last1=Kovacs | first1=N. | title=Model-atmosphere analysis of high-dispersion spectra of four red giants and supergiants | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=120 | issue=1 | pages=21\u201335 |date=April 1983 | bibcode=1983A&A...120...21K }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=scfs>{{citation | display-authors=1 | title=Sixth Catalogue of Fundamental Stars (FK6). Part I. Basic fundamental stars with direct solutions | journal=Ver\u00f6ff. Astron. Rechen-Inst. Heidelb | volume=35 | last1=Wielen | first1=R. | last2=Schwan | first2=H. | last3=Dettbarn | first3=C. | last4=Lenhardt | first4=H. | last5=Jahrei\u00df | first5=H. | last6=J\u00e4hrling | first6=R. | publisher=Astronomisches Rechen-Institut Heidelberg | issue=35 | date=1999 | bibcode=1999VeARI..35....1W }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=clpl4_99>{{cite journal | display-authors=1 | last1=Johnson | first1=H. L. | last2=Iriarte | first2=B. | last3=Mitchell | first3=R. I. | last4=Wisniewskj | first4=W. Z. | title=UBVRIJKL photometry of the bright stars | journal=Communications of the Lunar and Planetary Laboratory | volume=4 | issue=99 | pages=99 | date=1966 | bibcode=1966CoLPL...4...99J }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=brazil_flag>{{cite web | title=Astronomy of the Brazilian Flag | url=https://flagspot.net/flags/br_astro.html | publisher=FOTW Flags Of The World website | accessdate=2011-12-26 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=apj658_2_L107>{{citation | last1=Ayres | first1=Thomas R. | last2=Brown | first2=Alexander | last3=Harper | first3=Graham M. | title=\u03b1 TrA Junior | journal=The Astrophysical Journal | volume=658 | issue=2 | pages=L107\u2013L110 |date=April 2007 | doi=10.1086/514818 | bibcode=2007ApJ...658L.107A }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=ridpath1989>{{citation | first1=Ian | last1=Ridpath | title=Star tales | publisher=James Clarke & Co. | date=1989 | isbn=0-7188-2695-7 | page=125 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gFrdcTdeVaEC&pg=RA1-PA12 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=SIMBAD>{{citation | title=alf TrA -- Star | work=SIMBAD | publisher=[[Centre de Donn\u00e9es astronomiques de Strasbourg]] | url=http://simbad.u-strasbg.fr/simbad/sim-id?Ident=Alpha+Trianguli+Australis | accessdate=2011-12-26 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=csiro>{{citation|title=The Colour of Stars |date=December 21, 2004 |work=Australia Telescope, Outreach and Education |publisher=[[Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation]] |url=http://outreach.atnf.csiro.au/education/senior/astrophysics/photometry_colour.html |accessdate=2012-01-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222183238/http://outreach.atnf.csiro.au/education/senior/astrophysics/photometry_colour.html |archivedate=February 22, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{citation|first1=James B. |last1=Kaler |title=ATRIA (Alpha Trianguli Australis) |work=Stars |publisher=University of Illinois |url=http://www.astro.uiuc.edu/~kaler/sow/atria.html |accessdate=2011-12-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205192527/http://www.astro.uiuc.edu/~kaler/sow/atria.html |archivedate=2008-12-05 }}\n\n{{Stars of Triangulum Australe}}\n\n[[Category:Bayer objects|Trianguli Australis, Alpha]]\n[[Category:Henry Draper Catalogue objects|150798]]\n[[Category:Hipparcos objects|082273]]\n[[Category:K-type bright giants]]\n[[Category:Triangulum Australe]]\n[[Category:HR objects|6217]]\n[[Category:Durchmusterung objects|CD-68 02822]]\n[[Category:Stars with proper names]]\n", "text_old": "{{Starbox begin\n| name = \u03b1 Trianguli Australis<br>(Atria)\n}}\n{{Starbox image\n| image =\n     <div style=\"position: relative\">[[File:Triangulum Australe IAU.svg|250px|alt=Diagram showing star positions and boundaries of the Triangulum Australe constellation and its surroundings]]\n     <div style=\"position: absolute; left: 93px; top: 128px\">[[File:Cercle rouge 100%.svg|12px]]</div>\n     </div>\n| caption=Location of \u03b1 Trianguli Australis (circled)\n}}\n{{Starbox observe\n| epoch    = J2000\n| ra       = {{RA|16|48|39.89508}}<ref name=aaa474_2_653/>\n| dec      = {{DEC|\u201369|01|39.7626}}<ref name=aaa474_2_653/>\n| appmag_v = 1.91<ref name=scfs/>\n| constell = [[Triangulum Australe]]\n}}\n{{Starbox character\n| class    = K2&nbsp;IIb-IIIa<ref name=aaa120_1_21/>\n| b-v      = +1.44<ref name=clpl4_99/>\n| u-b      = +1.56<ref name=clpl4_99/>\n| variable =\n}}\n{{Starbox astrometry\n| radial_v    = \u20133.3<ref name=scfs/>\n| prop_mo_ra  = 17.99<ref name=aaa474_2_653/>\n| prop_mo_dec = \u201331.58<ref name=aaa474_2_653/>\n| parallax    = 8.35\n| p_error     = 0.15\n| parallax_footnote = <ref name=aaa474_2_653/>\n| absmag_v    = \u20133.68<ref name=apj658_2_L107/>\n}}\n{{Starbox detail\n| mass     = 7<ref name=aaa120_1_21/>\n| radius   =\n| luminosity  = 5,500<ref name=apj658_2_L107/>\n| gravity  = 1.5<ref name=aaa120_1_21/>\n| temperature = 4,150<ref name=aaa120_1_21/>\n| metal_fe = \u20130.06<ref name=aaa120_1_21/>\n| rotational_velocity =\n| age      = {{nowrap|4.8 \u00d7 10<sup>7</sup>}}<ref name=aaa120_1_21/>\n}}\n{{Starbox catalog\n| names=Atria, [[Harvard Revised catalogue|HR]] 6217,  [[Cordoba Durchmusterung|CD]] \u221268\u00b02822, [[Henry Draper catalogue|HD]] 150798, [[Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory Star Catalog|SAO]] 253700, [[Fifth Fundamental Catalogue|FK5]] 625, GC 22558, [[Hipparcos catalogue|HIP]] 82273.<ref name=SIMBAD/>\n}}\n{{Starbox reference\n| Simbad=Alpha+Trianguli+Australis\n}}\n{{Starbox end}}\n\n'''Alpha Trianguli Australis''' ([[Latinisation of names|Latinised]] from '''\u03b1 Trianguli Australis''', abbreviated '''Alpha TrA''', '''\u03b1 TrA'''), officially named '''Atria''' {{IPAc-en|'|ei|t|r|i|@}},<ref name=Kunitzsch>{{cite book\n  |last=Kunitzsch |first=Paul\n  |last2=Smart |first2=Tim\n  |date = 2006  |edition = 2nd rev.\n  |title = A Dictionary of Modern star Names: A Short Guide to 254 Star Names and Their Derivations\n  |publisher = Sky Pub |location = Cambridge, Massachusetts\n  |isbn = 978-1-931559-44-7\n}}</ref><ref name=\"IAU-CSN\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pas.rochester.edu/~emamajek/WGSN/IAU-CSN.txt | title=IAU Catalog of Star Names |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref> is the brightest [[star]] in the southern [[constellation]] of [[Triangulum Australe]], forming an apex of a triangle with [[Beta Trianguli Australis]] and [[Gamma Trianguli Australis]] that gives the constellation its name ([[Latin]] for southern triangle).\n\n==Nomenclature==\n\n''\u03b1 Trianguli Australis'' (Latinised to ''Alpha Trianguli Australis'') is the star's [[Bayer designation]]. The historical name ''Atria'' is a contraction.<ref name=ridpath1989/><ref name=\"kaleratria\">{{cite web|url=http://stars.astro.illinois.edu/sow/atria.html|title=Atria (Alpha Trianguli Australis) |last=Kaler|first=Jim|work=Stars|publisher=[[University of Illinois]]|accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref> In 2016, the [[International Astronomical Union]] organized a [[IAU Working Group on Star Names|Working Group on Star Names]] (WGSN)<ref name=\"WGSN\">{{cite web | url=https://www.iau.org/science/scientific_bodies/working_groups/280/ | title=IAU Working Group on Star Names (WGSN)|accessdate=22 May 2016}}</ref> to catalog and standardize proper names for stars. The WGSN's first bulletin of July 2016<ref name=\"WGSN1\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pas.rochester.edu/~emamajek/WGSN/WGSN_bulletin1.pdf | title=Bulletin of the IAU Working Group on Star Names, No. 1 |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref> included a table of the first two batches of names approved by the WGSN; which included ''Atria'' for this star.\n\nIn [[Chinese language|Chinese]] caused by adaptation of the European southern hemisphere constellations into the Chinese system, {{lang|zh|\u4e09\u89d2\u5f62}} ({{lang|zh-Latn|S\u0101n Ji\u01ceo X\u00edng}}), meaning ''[[Chinese constellations#The Southern Asterisms|Triangle]]'', refers to an asterism consisting of \u03b1 Trianguli Australis, \u03b2 Trianguli Australis and \u03b3 Trianguli Australis. Consequently, \u03b1 Trianguli Australis itself is known as {{lang|zh|\u4e09\u89d2\u5f62\u4e09}} ({{lang|zh-Latn|S\u0101n Ji\u01ceo X\u00edng s\u0101n}}, {{lang-en|the Third Star of Triangle}}.)<ref>{{in lang|zh}} [http://aeea.nmns.edu.tw/2006/0607/ap060729.html AEEA (Activities of Exhibition and Education in Astronomy) \u5929\u6587\u6559\u80b2\u8cc7\u8a0a\u7db2 2006 \u5e74 7 \u6708 29 \u65e5]</ref>\n\n==Physical characteristics==\n\nAlpha Trianguli Australis is a [[bright giant]] star with an [[apparent magnitude]] of +1.91. Based upon [[parallax]] measurements, this star is located roughly {{Convert|391|ly|pc|abbr=off|lk=on}} distant from the Earth.<ref name=aaa474_2_653/> The estimated age of the star is 48 million years old; sufficiently old for a massive star to evolve away from the [[main sequence]] and expand into a giant.<ref name=aaa120_1_21/> It has a mass roughly seven times the [[solar mass|mass of the Sun]], but is emitting about 5,500 times the [[solar luminosity|Sun's luminosity]]. The [[effective temperature]] of the star's outer envelope is 4,150&nbsp;K,<ref name=aaa120_1_21/> which gives it the characteristic orange hue of a K-type star.<ref name=csiro/> With a diameter 130 times [[Solar radius|that of the Sun]], it would almost reach the orbit of [[Venus]] if placed at the centre of the [[Solar System]].\n\nThere is evidence that Atria may be a [[binary star]]. It displays unusual properties for a star of its class, including [[flare star|stellar flares]] and a higher than normal emission of X-rays. These can be explained by a young, [[Stellar magnetic field|magnetically active]] companion with a [[stellar classification]] of about G0&nbsp;V. Such a star would have a mass similar to the Sun, with an orbital period of at least 130&nbsp;years. Young, [[G-type star]]s have a high temperature [[corona]] and frequently emit flares causing sudden increases in luminosity. The pair may be separated by about 50&nbsp;[[astronomical unit]]s.<ref name=apj658_2_L107/>\n\n==In culture==\nAtria appears on the [[flag of Brazil]], symbolizing the state of [[Rio Grande do Sul]].<ref name=brazil_flag/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=aaa474_2_653>{{cite journal | first=F. | last=van Leeuwen |date=November 2007 | title=Validation of the new Hipparcos reduction | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=474 | issue=2 | pages=653\u2013664 | bibcode=2007A&A...474..653V | doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20078357 |arxiv = 0708.1752 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=aaa120_1_21>{{citation | last1=Kovacs | first1=N. | title=Model-atmosphere analysis of high-dispersion spectra of four red giants and supergiants | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=120 | issue=1 | pages=21\u201335 |date=April 1983 | bibcode=1983A&A...120...21K }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=scfs>{{citation | display-authors=1 | title=Sixth Catalogue of Fundamental Stars (FK6). Part I. Basic fundamental stars with direct solutions | journal=Ver\u00f6ff. Astron. Rechen-Inst. Heidelb | volume=35 | last1=Wielen | first1=R. | last2=Schwan | first2=H. | last3=Dettbarn | first3=C. | last4=Lenhardt | first4=H. | last5=Jahrei\u00df | first5=H. | last6=J\u00e4hrling | first6=R. | publisher=Astronomisches Rechen-Institut Heidelberg | issue=35 | date=1999 | bibcode=1999VeARI..35....1W }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=clpl4_99>{{cite journal | display-authors=1 | last1=Johnson | first1=H. L. | last2=Iriarte | first2=B. | last3=Mitchell | first3=R. I. | last4=Wisniewskj | first4=W. Z. | title=UBVRIJKL photometry of the bright stars | journal=Communications of the Lunar and Planetary Laboratory | volume=4 | issue=99 | pages=99 | date=1966 | bibcode=1966CoLPL...4...99J }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=brazil_flag>{{cite web | title=Astronomy of the Brazilian Flag | url=https://flagspot.net/flags/br_astro.html | publisher=FOTW Flags Of The World website | accessdate=2011-12-26 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=apj658_2_L107>{{citation | last1=Ayres | first1=Thomas R. | last2=Brown | first2=Alexander | last3=Harper | first3=Graham M. | title=\u03b1 TrA Junior | journal=The Astrophysical Journal | volume=658 | issue=2 | pages=L107\u2013L110 |date=April 2007 | doi=10.1086/514818 | bibcode=2007ApJ...658L.107A }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=ridpath1989>{{citation | first1=Ian | last1=Ridpath | title=Star tales | publisher=James Clarke & Co. | date=1989 | isbn=0-7188-2695-7 | page=125 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gFrdcTdeVaEC&pg=RA1-PA12 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=SIMBAD>{{citation | title=alf TrA -- Star | work=SIMBAD | publisher=[[Centre de Donn\u00e9es astronomiques de Strasbourg]] | url=http://simbad.u-strasbg.fr/simbad/sim-id?Ident=Alpha+Trianguli+Australis | accessdate=2011-12-26 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=csiro>{{citation|title=The Colour of Stars |date=December 21, 2004 |work=Australia Telescope, Outreach and Education |publisher=[[Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation]] |url=http://outreach.atnf.csiro.au/education/senior/astrophysics/photometry_colour.html |accessdate=2012-01-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222183238/http://outreach.atnf.csiro.au/education/senior/astrophysics/photometry_colour.html |archivedate=February 22, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{citation|first1=James B. |last1=Kaler |title=ATRIA (Alpha Trianguli Australis) |work=Stars |publisher=University of Illinois |url=http://www.astro.uiuc.edu/~kaler/sow/atria.html |accessdate=2011-12-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205192527/http://www.astro.uiuc.edu/~kaler/sow/atria.html |archivedate=2008-12-05 }}\n\n{{Stars of Triangulum Australe}}\n\n[[Category:Bayer objects|Trianguli Australis, Alpha]]\n[[Category:Henry Draper Catalogue objects|150798]]\n[[Category:Hipparcos objects|082273]]\n[[Category:K-type bright giants]]\n[[Category:Triangulum Australe]]\n[[Category:HR objects|6217]]\n[[Category:Durchmusterung objects|CD-68 02822]]\n[[Category:Stars with proper names]]\n", "name_user": "Netoholic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePhysical characteristics:post-move link fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alpha_Trianguli_Australis"}
{"title_page": "List of Gregory Peck performances", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Gregory Peck Atticus Publicity Photo.jpg|thumb|alt=A black and white photograph of Peck as Atticus Finch in To Kill a Mockingbird|upright=1.2|Peck as [[Atticus Finch]] in a publicity photo for ''[[To Kill a Mockingbird (film)|To Kill a Mockingbird]]'' (1962)]]\n[[Gregory Peck]] (April 5, 1916 \u2013 June 12, 2003)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/06/12/obituaries/gregory-peck-a-star-of-quiet-dignity-dies-at-87.html|work=The New York Times|title=Gregory Peck, a Star of Quiet Dignity, Dies at 87|date=June 12, 2003|accessdate=February 22, 2020|last=Grimes|first=William}}</ref> was an American actor who had an extensive career in film, television, radio, and on stage. Peck's breakthrough role was as a [[Catholic]] priest who attempts to start a [[Christian mission|mission]] in China in the 1944 film ''[[The Keys of the Kingdom (film)|The Keys of the Kingdom]]'', for which he received his first nomination for the [[Academy Award for Best Actor]].{{sfn|Haney|2005|p=105}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1946|title=The 18th Academy Awards|publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> In the same year, he played Count Vronsky in a radio adaptation of [[Leo Tolstoy]]'s ''[[Anna Karenina]]''. He followed this by starring in [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s psychological thriller ''[[Spellbound (1945 film)|Spellbound]]'' (1945) with [[Ingrid Bergman]]. In the late 1940s, Peck received three more nominations for the Academy Award for Best Actor for his roles as a caring father in ''[[The Yearling (1946 film)|The Yearling]]'' (1946), a journalist who pretends to be Jewish to write an expos\u00e9 on American [[anti-semitism]] in ''[[Gentleman's Agreement]]'' (1947), and a brave airman in ''[[Twelve O'Clock High]]'' (1949).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1947|title=The 19th Academy Awards|publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1948|title=The 20th Academy Awards|publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1950|title=The 22nd Academy Awards|publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> \n\nPeck co-founded the theatre company [[La Jolla Playhouse]] in 1947 with [[Dorothy McGuire]] and [[Mel Ferrer]]. He starred in productions of ''[[Gas Light|Angel Street]]'' and ''The Male Animal'' for the company.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2003/jun/14/guardianobituaries.film|work=The Guardian|title=Gregory Peck obituary|last=Bergan|first=Ronald|date=June 14, 2003|accessdate=February 23, 2020}}</ref> In 1951, he played Royal Navy officer [[Horatio Hornblower]] in the [[Captain Horatio Hornblower|eponymous film]], [[David]] in the biblical epic ''[[David and Bathsheba (film)|David and Bathsheba]]'' with [[Susan Hayward]], and a soldier in the western ''[[Only the Valiant]]'' with [[Barbara Payton]]. Two years later, Peck appeared as a journalist who falls in love with a princess in the romantic comedy ''[[Roman Holiday]]'' (1953) with [[Audrey Hepburn]]. During the late 1950s, he portrayed [[Captain Ahab]] in ''[[Moby Dick (1956 film)|Moby Dick]]'' (1956), war hero [[Joseph G. Clemons]] in ''[[Pork Chop Hill]]'' (1959), and writer [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]] in ''[[Beloved Infidel]]'' (1959).<ref name=Ahab/>{{sfn|p=428|Haney|2005}} \n\nHe won the [[Academy Award for Best Actor]] for his performance as [[Atticus Finch]], a lawyer attempting to exonerate a black man wrongly accused of rape in courtroom drama ''[[To Kill a Mockingbird (film)|To Kill a Mockingbird]]'' (1962).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1963|title=The 35th Academy Awards|accessdate=February 22, 2020|publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences}}</ref> The role topped the [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Heroes & Villains|AFI's 50 Greatest Screen Heroes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afi.com/afis-100-years-100-heroes-villians/|title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Heroes & Villains|publisher=American Film Institute|accessdate=February 23, 2020}}</ref> Seven years later, he appeared in the title role of the western ''[[Mackenna's Gold]]'', and as a spy in ''[[The Chairman (1969 film)|The Chairman]]''.<ref name=Mackenna/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/film/fwhp64/the-chairman/|work=Radio Times|title=The Chairman|last=Jones|first=Alan|accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref> In the late 1970s, Peck played General [[Douglas MacArthur]] in the [[MacArthur (film)|eponymous 1977 film]] and Nazi doctor [[Josef Mengele]] in ''[[The Boys from Brazil (film)|The Boys from Brazil]]'' (1978).<ref name=MacArthur/><ref name=Brazil/> \n    \nPeck made his television debut in 1982 by appearing as President [[Abraham Lincoln]] in the miniseries ''[[The Blue and the Gray (miniseries)|The Blue and the Gray]]''.<ref name=Guardian/> He followed this with the television film ''[[The Scarlet and the Black]]'' where he portrayed Catholic priest [[Hugh O'Flaherty]] who helped Jews and prisoners of war to hide in World War II-era Rome.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/msgr-hugh-o-flaherty-the-most-remarkable-irish-cleric-you-ve-never-heard-of-1.3604096|work=The Irish Times|date=August 23, 2018|accessdate=February 22, 2020|last=Murphy|first=Patricia|title=Msgr Hugh O\u2019Flaherty, the most remarkable Irish cleric you\u2019ve never heard of}}</ref> For his appearance as Father Mapple in the 1998 miniseries ''[[Moby Dick (1998 miniseries)|Moby Dick]]'', he received the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film]] and a nomination for a [[Primetime Emmy Award|Primetime Emmy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/person/gregory-peck|title=Gregory Peck|publisher=[[Hollywood Foreign Press Association]]|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/shows/moby-dick|title=Moby Dick|accessdate=February 23, 2020|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]}}</ref>\n\n==Film==\n[[File:Peck_Publicity_Photo_1944.jpg|alt=A black and white photograph in a publicity photograph for The Keys of the Kingdom|thumb|upright=1.0|In ''[[The Keys of the Kingdom (film)|The Keys of the Kingdom]]'' (1944)]]\n[[File:Only the Valiant (1951) 2.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|alt=A black and white photograph of Peck with Barbara Payton in Only the Valiant|With [[Barbara Payton]] (right) in ''[[Only the Valiant]]'' (1951)]]\n[[File:Hepburn Peck Promo.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|alt=A black and white photograph of Peck with Audrey Hepburn in Roman Holiday|With [[Audrey Hepburn]] (left) in ''[[Roman Holiday]]'' (1953)]]\n[[File:Peck Moby Dick.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|alt=A black and white photograph of Peck as Captain Ahab in Moby Dick|[[Captain Ahab]] in ''[[Moby Dick (1956 film)|Moby Dick]]'' (1956)]]\n<!-- Please DO NOT add rowspans as they break the sorting and are not meant to be used in a sortable wikitable. The tables, as they stand right now, are in the preferred formatting. -->\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Year\n!scope=\"col\"|Title\n!scope=\"col\"|Role(s)\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n!scope=row|1944\n|''[[Days of Glory (1944 film)|Days of Glory]]''\n|Vladimir\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1944/06/17/archives/days-of-glory-starring-tamara-toumanova-and-gregory-peck-at-palace.html|work=The New York Times|date=June 17, 1944|accessdate=December 31, 2019|last=Crowther|title=' Days of Glory,' Starring Tamara Tou