5395-9|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Haney|first=Lynn|title=Gregory Peck: A Charmed Life|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9MbEOmfg4PcC|date=March 24, 2005|publisher=Pavilion Books|isbn=978-1-86105-824-9|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Molyneaux|first=Gerard|title=Gregory Peck: A Bio-bibliography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VUrUeKBmnUYC|year=1995|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-28668-1}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0000060|Gregory Peck}}\n\n[[Category:Male actor filmographies|Peck, Gregory]]\n[[Category:American filmographies|Peck, Gregory]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Gregory Peck Atticus Publicity Photo.jpg|thumb|alt=A black and white photograph of Peck as Atticus Finch in To Kill a Mockingbird|upright=1.2|Peck as [[Atticus Finch]] in a publicity photo for ''[[To Kill a Mockingbird (film)|To Kill a Mockingbird]]'' (1962)]]\n[[Gregory Peck]] (April 5, 1916 \u2013 June 12, 2003)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/06/12/obituaries/gregory-peck-a-star-of-quiet-dignity-dies-at-87.html|work=The New York Times|title=Gregory Peck, a Star of Quiet Dignity, Dies at 87|date=June 12, 2003|accessdate=February 22, 2020|last=Grimes|first=William}}</ref> was an American actor who had an extensive career in film, television, radio, and on stage. Peck's breakthrough role was as a [[Catholic]] priest who attempts to start a [[Christian mission|mission]] in China in the 1944 film ''[[The Keys of the Kingdom (film)|The Keys of the Kingdom]]'', for which he received his first nomination for the [[Academy Award for Best Actor]].{{sfn|Haney|2005|p=105}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1946|title=The 18th Academy Awards|publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> In the same year, he played Count Vronsky in a radio adaptation of [[Leo Tolstoy]]'s ''[[Anna Karenina]]''. He followed this by starring in [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s psychological thriller ''[[Spellbound (1945 film)|Spellbound]]'' (1945) with [[Ingrid Bergman]]. In the late 1940s, Peck received three more nominations for the Academy Award for Best Actor for his roles as a caring father in ''[[The Yearling (1946 film)|The Yearling]]'' (1946), a journalist who pretends to be Jewish to write an expos\u00e9 on American [[anti-semitism]] in ''[[Gentleman's Agreement]]'' (1947), and a brave airman in ''[[Twelve O'Clock High]]'' (1949).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1947|title=The 19th Academy Awards|publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1948|title=The 20th Academy Awards|publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1950|title=The 22nd Academy Awards|publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> \n\nPeck co-founded the theatre company [[La Jolla Playhouse]] in 1947 with [[Dorothy McGuire]] and [[Mel Ferrer]]. He starred in productions of ''[[Gas Light|Angel Street]]'' and ''The Male Animal'' for the company.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2003/jun/14/guardianobituaries.film|work=The Guardian|title=Gregory Peck obituary|last=Bergan|first=Ronald|date=June 14, 2003|accessdate=February 23, 2020}}</ref> In 1951, he played Royal Navy officer [[Horatio Hornblower]] in the [[Captain Horatio Hornblower|eponymous film]], [[David]] in the biblical epic ''[[David and Bathsheba (film)|David and Bathsheba]]'' with [[Susan Hayward]], and a soldier in the western ''[[Only the Valiant]]'' with [[Barbara Payton]]. Two years later, Peck appeared as a journalist who falls in love with a princess in the romantic comedy ''[[Roman Holiday]]'' (1953) with [[Audrey Hepburn]]. During the late 1950s, he portrayed [[Captain Ahab]] in ''[[Moby Dick (1956 film)|Moby Dick]]'' (1956), war hero [[Joseph G. Clemons]] in ''[[Pork Chop Hill]]'' (1959), and writer [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]] in ''[[Beloved Infidel]]'' (1959).<ref name=Ahab/>{{sfn|p=428|Haney|2005}} \n\nHe won the [[Academy Award for Best Actor]] for his performance as [[Atticus Finch]], a lawyer attempting to exonerate a black man wrongly accused of rape in courtroom drama ''[[To Kill a Mockingbird (film)|To Kill a Mockingbird]]'' (1962).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1963|title=The 35th Academy Awards|accessdate=February 22, 2020|publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences}}</ref> The role topped the [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Heroes & Villains|AFI's 50 Greatest Screen Heroes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afi.com/afis-100-years-100-heroes-villians/|title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Heroes & Villains|publisher=American Film Institute|accessdate=February 23, 2020}}</ref> Seven years later, he appeared in the title role of the western ''[[Mackenna's Gold]]'', and as a spy in ''[[The Chairman (1969 film)|The Chairman]]''.<ref name=Mackenna/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/film/fwhp64/the-chairman/|work=Radio Times|title=The Chairman|last=Jones|first=Alan|accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref> In the late 1970s, Peck played General [[Douglas MacArthur]] in the [[MacArthur (film)|eponymous 1977 film]] and Nazi doctor [[Josef Mengele]] in ''[[The Boys from Brazil (film)|The Boys from Brazil]]'' (1978).<ref name=MacArthur/><ref name=Brazil/> \n    \nPeck made his television debut in 1982 by appearing as President [[Abraham Lincoln]] in the miniseries ''[[The Blue and the Gray (miniseries)|The Blue and the Gray]]''.<ref name=Guardian/> He followed this with the television film ''[[The Scarlet and the Black]]'' where he portrayed Catholic priest [[Hugh O'Flaherty]] who helped Jews and prisoners of war to hide in World War II-era Rome.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/msgr-hugh-o-flaherty-the-most-remarkable-irish-cleric-you-ve-never-heard-of-1.3604096|work=The Irish Times|date=August 23, 2018|accessdate=February 22, 2020|last=Murphy|first=Patricia|title=Msgr Hugh O\u2019Flaherty, the most remarkable Irish cleric you\u2019ve never heard of}}</ref> For his appearance as Father Mapple in the 1998 miniseries ''[[Moby Dick (1998 miniseries)|Moby Dick]]'', he received the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film]] and a nomination for a [[Primetime Emmy Award|Primetime Emmy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/person/gregory-peck|title=Gregory Peck|publisher=[[Hollywood Foreign Press Association]]|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/shows/moby-dick|title=Moby Dick|accessdate=February 23, 2020|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]}}</ref>\n\n===Film===\n[[File:Peck_Publicity_Photo_1944.jpg|alt=A black and white photograph in a publicity photograph for The Keys of the Kingdom|thumb|upright=1.0|In ''[[The Keys of the Kingdom (film)|The Keys of the Kingdom]]'' (1944)]]\n[[File:Only the Valiant (1951) 2.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|alt=A black and white photograph of Peck with Barbara Payton in Only the Valiant|With [[Barbara Payton]] (right) in ''[[Only the Valiant]]'' (1951)]]\n[[File:Hepburn Peck Promo.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|alt=A black and white photograph of Peck with Audrey Hepburn in Roman Holiday|With [[Audrey Hepburn]] (left) in ''[[Roman Holiday]]'' (1953)]]\n[[File:Peck Moby Dick.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|alt=A black and white photograph of Peck as Captain Ahab in Moby Dick|[[Captain Ahab]] in ''[[Moby Dick (1956 film)|Moby Dick]]'' (1956)]]\n<!-- Please DO NOT add rowspans as they break the sorting and are not meant to be used in a sortable wikitable. The tables, as they stand right now, are in the preferred formatting. -->\n{| class=\"wiki