2_1_161/>\n | metal_fe = 0.05<ref name=aaa501_3_941/>\n | age_gyr  = 1.1<ref name=aaa501_3_941/>\n | luminosity = 17.7<ref name=aaa409_251/>\n | temperature = 6,519<ref name=aj132_1_161/>\n | rotational_velocity = 150.0<ref name=aaa409_251/>\n}}\n{{Starbox catalog\n | names = [[Bayer designation|&eta;]]&nbsp;Sco, [[Cordoba Durchmusterung|CD]]-43&nbsp;11485, [[Fifth Fundamental Catalogue|FK5]]&nbsp;638, [[Gliese Catalogue of Nearby Stars|GJ]]&nbsp;657, [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]]&nbsp;155203, [[Hipparcos|HIP]]&nbsp;84143, [[Star catalogue#BS, BSC, HR|HR]]&nbsp;6380, [[Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory catalogue|SAO]]&nbsp;227707.<ref name=SIMBAD/>\n}}\n{{Starbox reference\n|Simbad=eta+Sco\n}}\n{{Starbox end}}\n'''Eta Scorpii''' (\u03b7 Sco, \u03b7 Scorpii) is a [[star]] in the southern [[zodiac]] [[constellation]] of [[Scorpius]]. With an [[apparent visual magnitude]] of 3.33,<ref name=aj77_733/> this is one of the [[List of stars in Scorpius|brighter members]] of the Scorpius and is the furthest south of the constellation stars with a [[Bayer designation]].<ref name=burnham1978/> The distance to this star can be estimated using [[parallax]] measurements, yielding a value of {{Convert|73.5|ly|pc|abbr=off|lk=on}} with a 0.4% [[margin of error]].<ref name=aaa474_2_653/>\n\nThe [[stellar classification]] of this star has undergone some revision over time, with the star being classified anywhere from an [[F-type main sequence star]] to a [[giant star]].<ref name=SIMBAD/> In 2006, the [[NStars]] program assigned it a class of F5&nbsp;IV,<ref name=aj132_1_161/> where the [[luminosity class]] of 'IV' indicates this is a [[subgiant star]] that is exhausting the supply of hydrogen at its core and is in the process of [[stellar evolution|evolving]] into a [[giant star]]. It has around 175%<ref name=aaa409_251/> of the Sun's mass with an estimated age of 1.1 billion years.<ref name=aaa501_3_941/> The star is radiating about 18<ref name=aaa409_251/> times the luminosity of the Sun from its outer atmosphere at an [[effective temperature]] of 6,519&nbsp;K.<ref name=aj132_1_161/> It is this heat that gives it a yellow-white hue that is typical for an F-type star.<ref name=csiro/>\n\nEta Scorpii is rotating rapidly, with a [[projected rotational velocity]] of {{nowrap|150 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>}}.<ref name=aaa409_251/> This is causing the star to spin on its axis with a period of less than a day.<ref name=kaler/> It is an X-ray emitter with its stellar [[corona]] giving off an X-ray luminosity of {{nowrap|4.4 \u00d7 10<sup>28</sup> ergs s<sup>\u22121</sup>}}.<ref name=aaa361_614/> In 1991 it was identified as a possible [[barium star]], as it displays an enhanced abundance of the element barium in its [[stellar spectrum|spectrum]].<ref name=aj101_2229/> Overall, the abundance of elements other than hydrogen and helium, what astronomers term the star's metallicity, is similar to the abundance in the Sun.<ref name=aaa501_3_941/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=aaa474_2_653>{{citation | first=F. | last=van Leeuwen |date=November 2007 | title=Validation of the new Hipparcos reduction | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=474 | issue=2 | pages=653\u2013664 | bibcode=2007A&A...474..653V | doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20078357 |arxiv = 0708.1752 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=rgcrv>{{citation | last=Evans | first=D. S. | date=June 20\u201324, 1966 | editor1=Batten, Alan Henry |editor2=Heard, John Frederick | title=The Revision of the General Catalogue of Radial Velocities | booktitle=Determination of Radial Velocities and their Applications, Proceedings from IAU Symposium no. 30 | location=University of Toronto | publisher=[[International Astronomical Union]] | bibcode=1967IAUS...30...57E }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=aaa361_614>{{citation | last1=Pizzolato | first1=N. | last2=Maggio | first2=A. | last3=Sciortino | first3=S. | title=Evolution of X-ray activity of 1-3 Msun late-type stars in early post-main-sequence phases | journal=Astronomy an